{"title_page": "LaVeyan Satanism", "text_new": "{{short description|Atheistic religion founded by Anton LaVey, in which Satan is a symbol of human freedom, but not believed to be a separately existing supernatural being}}\n[[File:Baphosimb.svg|thumb|right|The Sigil of Baphomet is the official [[Religious symbol|symbol]] of LaVeyan Satanism and the Church of Satan.]]\n'''LaVeyan Satanism''' is a [[religion]] founded in 1966 by the American [[occultism|occultist]] and author [[Anton LaVey|Anton Szandor LaVey]]. Scholars of religion have classified it as a [[new religious movement]] and a form of [[Western esotericism]]. It is one of several different movements that describe themselves as forms of [[Satanism]].\n\nLaVey established LaVeyan Satanism in the U.S. state of [[California]] through the founding of his [[Church of Satan]] on [[Walpurgisnacht]] of 1966, which he proclaimed to be \"the Year One\", ''Anno Satanas''\u2014the first year of the \"Age of Satan\". His ideas were heavily influenced by the ideas and writings of [[Friedrich Nietzsche]] and [[Ayn Rand]]. The church grew under LaVey's leadership, with regional ''[[Grotto (Satanism)|grottos]]'' being founded across the United States. A number of these seceded from the church to form independent Satanic organizations during the early 1970s. In 1975, LaVey abolished the grotto system, after which Satanism became a far less organized movement, although it remained greatly influenced by LaVey's writings. In coming years, members of the church left it to establish their own organisations, also following LaVeyan Satanism, among them John Dewey Allee's First Church of Satan and [[Karla LaVey]]'s [[First Satanic Church]].\n\nThe religion's doctrines are codified in LaVey's book, ''[[The Satanic Bible]]''. The religion is [[materialist]], rejecting the existence of supernatural beings, [[Dualism (philosophy of mind)|body-soul dualism]], and [[Afterlife|life after death]]. Practitioners do not believe that [[Satan]] literally exists and do not worship him. Instead, Satan is viewed as a positive archetype representing [[pride]], [[wiktionary:carnal|carnality]], and [[Age of Enlightenment|enlightenment]]. He is also embraced as a [[symbol]] of defiance against [[Abrahamic religions]] which LaVeyans criticize for suppressing humanity's natural instincts and encouraging irrationality. The religion propagates a [[Naturalism (philosophy)|naturalistic]] worldview, seeing mankind as animals existing in an [[amorality|amoral]] universe. It promotes a philosophy based on [[individualism]] and [[rational egoism|egoism]], coupled with [[Social Darwinism]] and [[anti-egalitarianism]].\n\nLaVeyan Satanism involves the practice of [[Magic (paranormal)|magic]], which encompasses two distinct forms; [[greater and lesser magic]]. Greater magic is a form of [[ritual]] practice and is meant as [[psychodramatic]] [[catharsis]] to focus one's emotional energy for a specific purpose. These rites are based on three major psycho-emotive themes: ''compassion'' ([[love]]), ''destruction'' ([[hate]]), and ''sex'' ([[lust]]).  Lesser magic is the practice of [[Psychological manipulation|manipulation]] by means of [[applied psychology]] and [[Glamour (presentation)|glamour]] (or [[Deception|\"wile and guile\"]]) to bend an individual or situation to one's will. Don\u2019t believe every little detail someone puts on a wiki mom... aka s.a.w.\n\n==Definition==\n{{LaVeyan Satanism sidebar}}\nLaVeyan Satanism &ndash; which is also sometimes termed \"Modern Satanism\"{{sfnm|1a1=Lap|1y=2013|1p=83|2a1=Dyrendal|2y=2013|2p=124}} and \"Rational Satanism\"{{sfnm|1a1=Petersen|1y=2009|1p=224|2a1=Dyrendal|2y=2013|2p=123}} &ndash; is classified by scholars of [[religious studies]] as a [[new religious movement]].{{sfn|Faxneld|Petersen|2013||p=81}} When used, \"Rational Satanism\" is often employed to distinguish the approach of the LaVeyan Satanists from the \"Esoteric Satanism\" embraced by groups like the [[Temple of Set]].{{sfnm|1a1=Dyrendal|1y=2012|1p=370|2a1=Petersen|2y=2012|2p=95}} A number of religious studies scholars have also described it as a form of \"self-religion\" or \"self-spirituality\",{{sfnm|1a1=Harvey|1y=1995|1p=290|2a1=Partridge|2y=2004|2p=82|3a1=Petersen|3y=2009|3pp=224&ndash;225|4a1=Schipper|4y=2010|4p=108|5a1=Faxneld|5a2=Petersen|5y=2013|5p=79}} with religious studies scholar Amina Olander Lap arguing that it should be seen as being both part of the \"prosperity wing\" of the self-spirituality [[New Age]] movement and a form of the [[Human Potential Movement]].{{sfn|Lap|2013|p=84}} Conversely, the scholar of Satanism Jesper Aa. Petersen preferred to treat modern Satanism as a \"cousin\" of the New Age and Human Potential movements.{{sfn|Petersen|2005|p=424}}\n\n{{Quote box\n| title = \n| quote = \"In LaVey's way of thinking, Satanism is both a distinctly new religion, which he himself, without any false modesty, invented and the continuance of an ancient tradition of opposition to the status quo... For LaVey, Satanism is also the religion of the playful provocateur; anything that will shock people out of their unthinking adherence to the status quo is worth thinking about or even doing.\"\n| source = Religious studies scholar Eugene Gallagher.{{sfn|Gallagher|2006|p=165}}\n| align = left\n| width = 30em\n| border = 1px\n| fontsize = 85%\n| title_bg = \n| title_fnt = \n| salign = right\n}}\n\nThe anthropologist Jean La Fontaine described LaVeyan Satanism as having \"both elitist and anarchist elements\", also citing one occult bookshop owner who referred to the church's approach as \"anarchistic hedonism\".{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=96}} In their study of Satanism, the [[religious studies]] scholars Asbj\u00f8rn Dyrendal, [[James R. Lewis (scholar)|James R. Lewis]], and Jesper Aa. Petersen suggested that LaVey viewed his religion as \"an antinomian self-religion for productive misfits, with a cynically [[carnivalesque]] take on life, and no supernaturalism\".{{sfn|Dyrendal|Lewis|Petersen|2016|p=70}} The sociologist of religion [[James R. Lewis (scholar)|James R. Lewis]] even described LaVeyan Satanism as \"a blend of Epicureanism and Ayn Rand's philosophy, flavored with a pinch of ritual magic.\"{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=2}} The historian of religion [[Mattias Gardell]] described LaVey's as \"a rational ideology of egoistic hedonism and self-preservation\",{{sfn|Gardell|2003|p=288}} while [[Nevill Drury]] characterised LaVeyan Satanism as \"a religion of self-indulgence\".{{sfn|Drury|2003|p=188}} It has also been described as an \"institutionalism of [[Niccol\u00f2 Machiavelli|Machiavellian]] self-interest\".{{sfn|Taub|Nelson|1993|p=528}}\n\nThe Church of Satan rejects the legitimacy of any other organizations who claim to be Satanists, dubbing them \"Devil worshipers\".<ref name=Stop>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/national/wp/2014/11/07/the-church-of-satan-wants-you-to-stop-calling-these-devil-worshipping-alleged-murderers-satanists/|title=The Church of Satan wants you to stop calling these 'devil worshiping' alleged murderers Satanists |date=7 November 2014 |website=The Washington Post |last=Ohlheiser |first=Abby |accessdate=2015-11-19}}</ref> Prominent Church leader [[Blanche Barton]] described Satanism as \"an alignment, a lifestyle\".{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=99}} LaVey and the church espoused the view that \"Satanists are born, not made\";{{sfn|Contemporary Religious Satanism: A Critical Anthology|Petersen|2009|p=9}} that they are outsiders by their nature, living as they see fit,{{sfn|The Devil's Party: Satanism in Modernity|Faxneld, Petersen|2013|p=129}} who are self-realized in a religion which appeals to the would-be Satanist's nature, leading them to realize they are Satanists through finding a belief system that is in line with their own perspective and lifestyle.{{sfn|Satanism Today|Lewis|2001|p=330}}\n\n==Belief==\n\n===''The Satanic Bible''===\n{{main|The Satanic Bible}}\n\n''The Satanic Bible'' has been in print since 1969 and has been translated into various languages.{{sfn|Lap|2013|p=85}} Lewis argued that although LaVeyan Satanists do not treat ''The Satanic Bible'' as a sacred text in the way many other religious groups treat their holy texts, it nevertheless is \"treated as an authoritative document which effectively ''functions'' as scripture within the Satanic community\".{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=2}} In particular, Lewis highlighted that many Satanists &ndash; both members of the Church of Satan and other groups &ndash; quote from it either to legitimize their own position or to de-legitimize the positions of others in a debate.{{sfn|Lewis|2002|pp=2, 13}} Many other Satanist groups and individual Satanists who are not part of the Church of Satan also recognize LaVey's work as influential.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=317}}\n\nMany Satanists attribute their conversions or discoveries of Satanism to ''The Satanic Bible'', with 20 percent of respondents to a survey by James Lewis mentioning ''The Satanic Bible'' directly as influencing their conversion.{{sfn|Lewis|2003|p=117}} For members of the church, the book is said to serve not only as a compendium of ideas but also to judge the authenticity of someone's claim to be a Satanist.{{sfn|The Devil's Party: Satanism in Modernity|Faxneld, Petersen|2013|page=115}} LaVey's writings have been described as \"cornerstones\" within the church and its teachings,{{sfn|Petersen|2012|p=114}} and have been supplemented with the writings of its later High Priest, Gilmore, namely his book, ''[[The Satanic Scriptures]]''.{{sfn|Petersen|2012|p=114}}\n\n''The Satanic Bible'' has been described as the most important document to influence contemporary Satanism.{{sfn|Lewis|2003|p = 116}} The book contains the core principles of Satanism, and is considered the foundation of its philosophy and dogma.{{sfn|Lewis|2003|p = 105}} On their website, the Church of Satan urge anyone seeking to learn about LaVeyan Satanism to read ''The Satanic Bible'', stating that doing so is \"tantamount to understanding at least the basics of Satanism\".{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=12}} Petersen noted that it is \"in many ways ''the'' central text of the Satanic milieu\",{{sfn|Petersen|2013|p=232}} with Lap similarly testifying to its dominant position within the wider Satanic movement.{{sfn|Lap|2013|p=85}} [[David G. Bromley]] calls it \"[[Iconoclasm|iconoclastic]]\" and \"the best-known and most influential statement of Satanic theology.\"{{sfn|Bromley|2005|pp=8127\u20138128}} [[Eugene V. Gallagher]] says that Satanists use LaVey's writings \"as lenses through which they view themselves, their group, and the cosmos.\" He also states: \"With a clear-eyed appreciation of true human nature, a love of ritual and pageantry, and a flair for mockery, LaVey's ''Satanic Bible'' promulgated a gospel of self-indulgence that, he argued, anyone who dispassionately considered the facts would embrace.\"{{sfn|Gallagher|2005|p=6530}}\n\n===Atheism and Satan===\n\nLaVey was an [[atheism|atheist]], rejecting the existence of all gods.<ref name=DwD>{{cite web |url=https://www.ozy.com/true-story/my-dinner-with-the-devil/71233/|title=My Dinner With The Devil |date=7 September 2016 |website=OZY |last=Robinson |first=Eugene |accessdate=2018-07-13}}</ref> LaVey and his Church do not espouse a belief in [[Satan]] as an entity who literally exists,{{sfn|Harvey|1995|p=290}} and LaVey did not encourage the worship of Satan as a deity.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=97}} Instead, the use of Satan as a central figure is intentionally symbolic.{{sfn|Petersen|2005|p=430}} LaVey sought to cement his belief system within the [[secularism|secularist]] world-view that derived from [[natural science]], thus providing him with an atheistic basis with which to criticize Christianity and other supernaturalist beliefs.{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2002|1p=4|2a1=Petersen|2y=2005|2p=434}} He legitimized his religion by highlighting what he claimed was its rational nature, contrasting this with what he saw as the supernaturalist irrationality of established religions.{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=4}} He defined Satanism as \"a secular philosophy of rationalism and self-preservation (natural law, animal state), giftwrapping these ideas in religious trappings to add to their appeal.\"{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=336}} In this way, LaVeyan Satanism has been described as an \"antireligious religion\" by van Luijk.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=328}} LaVey did not believe in any [[afterlife]].{{sfn|Maxwell-Stuart|2011|p=198}}\n\n{{Quote box\n| title = \n| quote = If man insists on externalizing his true self in the form of \"God,\" then why fear his true self, in fearing \"God,\"\u2014why praise his true self in praising \"God,\"\u2014why remain externalized from \"God\" {{smallcaps|in order to engage in ritual and religious ceremony in his name?}}<br />Man needs ritual and dogma, but no law states that an ''externalized'' god is necessary in order to engage in ritual and ceremony performed in a god's name! Could it be that when he closes the gap between himself and his \"God\" he sees the demon of pride creeping forth\u2014that very embodiment of Lucifer appearing in his midst?\n| source = LaVey, ''The Satanic Bible''.{{sfn|Harvey|1995|p=291}}\n| align = right\n| width = 30em\n| border = 1px\n| fontsize = 85%\n| title_bg = \n| title_fnt = \n| salign = right\n}}\n\nInstead of worshiping the Devil as a real figure, the image of Satan is embraced because of its association with social non-conformity and rebellion against the dominant system.{{sfnm|1a1=Harvey|1y=1995|1p=290|2a1=La Fontaine|2y=1999|2p=97}} LaVey embraced the iconography of Satan and the label of \"Satanist\" because it shocked people into thinking,{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2001a|1p=17|2a1=Gallagher|2y=2006|2p=165}} and when asked about his religion, stated that \"the reason it's called Satanism is because it's fun, it's accurate and it's productive\".{{sfn|Harvey|1995|p=290}}\n\nLaVey also conceptualised Satan as a symbol of the individual's own vitality,{{sfn|Schipper|2010|p=107}} thus representing an autonomous power within,{{sfn|Schipper|2010|p=106}} and a representation of personal liberty and individualism.{{sfn|Cavaglion|Sela-Shayovitz|2005|p=255}} Throughout ''The Satanic Bible'', the LaVeyan Satanist's view of god is described as the Satanist's true \"self\"\u2014a projection of his or her own personality\u2014not an external deity.{{sfn|Wright|1993|p=143}} In works like ''The Satanic Bible'', LaVey often uses the terms \"god\" and \"Satan\" interchangeably, viewing both as personifications of human nature.{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=287|2a1=Muzzatti|2y=2005|2p=874}}\n\nDespite his professed atheism, some passages of LaVey's writings left room for a literal interpretation of Satan, and some members of his Church understood the Devil as an entity that really existed.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=348}} It is possible that LaVey left some ambivalence in his writings so as not to drive away those Church members who were theistic Satanists.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=355}}\nBoth LaVey's writings and the publications of the church continue to refer to Satan as if he were a real being, in doing so seeking to reinforce the Satanist's self-interest.{{sfn|Harvey|1995|p=291}}\n\nLaVey used Christianity as a negative mirror for his new faith,{{sfn|Schipper|2010|p=109}} with LaVeyan Satanism rejecting the basic principles and theology of Christian belief.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=96}} It views Christianity &ndash; alongside other major religions, and philosophies such as [[humanism]] and [[liberal democracy]] &ndash; as a largely negative force on humanity; LaVeyan Satanists perceive Christianity as a lie which promotes idealism, self-denigration, herd behavior, and irrationality.{{sfn|Faxneld|Petersen|2013|p=80}} LaVeyans view their religion as a force for redressing this balance by encouraging materialism, egoism, stratification, carnality, atheism, and social Darwinism.{{sfn|Faxneld|Petersen|2013|p=80}} LaVey's Satanism was particularly critical of what it understands as Christianity's denial of humanity's animal nature, and it instead calls for the celebration of, and indulgence in, these desires.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=96}} In doing so, it places an emphasis on the carnal rather than the spiritual.{{sfn|Lewis|2001b|p=50}}\n\n===Human nature and society===\n\nLaVeyan Satanism has been characterised as belonging to the [[Right-wing politics|political right]] rather than to the [[Left-wing politics|political left]].{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=326}} The historian of Satanism Ruben van Luijk characterised it as a form of \"anarchism of the Right\".{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=374}} LaVey was anti-egalitarian and elitist, believing in the fundamental inequality of different human beings.{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=289|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=366}} His philosophy was [[Social Darwinist]] in basis,{{sfnm|1a1=La Fontaine|1y=1999|1p=97|2a1=Lap|2y=2013|2p=95|3a1=van Luijk|3y=2016|3p=367}} having been influenced by the writings of [[Herbert Spencer]], [[Friedrich Nietzsche]], and [[Ayn Rand]].{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=287|2a1=Petersen|2y=2005|2p=447|3a1=Lap|3y=2013|3p=95}} LaVey stated that his Satanism was \"just Ayn Rand's philosophy with ceremony and ritual added\".{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2001a|1p=18|2a1=Lewis|2y=2002|2p=9}} Characterising LaVey as a Nietzschean, the religious studies scholar Asbj\u00f8rn Dyrendal nevertheless thought that LaVey's \"personal synthesis seems decidedly his own creation, even though the different ingredients going into it are at times very visible.\"{{sfn|Dyrendal|2012|p=370}} Social Darwinism is particularly noticeable in ''The Book of Satan'', where LaVey uses portions of Redbeard's ''[[Might Is Right]]'', though it also appears throughout in references to man's inherent strength and instinct for self-preservation.{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=4}}\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = left\n\n | image1 = Nietzsche187a.jpg\n | alt1 = Friedrich Nietzsche\n | link1 = [Friedrich Nietzsche]\n\n | image2 = \n | alt2 = Ayn Rand\n | link2 = [Ayn Rand]\n \n| footer = LaVeyan Satanism's views on human nature are influenced by the work of [[Friedrich Nietzsche]] (''pictured'') and [[Ayn Rand]].\n}}\n\nFor LaVey, the human being was explicitly viewed as an animal,{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2002|1p=4|2a1=Gardell|2y=2003|2p=288|3a1=Baddeley|3y=2010|3p=74|4a1=Lap|4y=2013|4p=94}} who thus has no purpose other than [[survival of the fittest]], and who therefore exists in an [[amorality|amoral]] context.{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=4}} He believed that in adopting a philosophical belief in its own superiority above that of the other animals, humankind has become \"the most vicious animal of all\".{{sfn|Lap|2013|p=94}} For LaVey, non-human animals and children represent an ideal, \"the purest form of carnal existence\", because they have not been indoctrinated with Christian or other religious concepts of guilt and shame.{{sfn|Lap|2013|p=95}} His ethical views focused around placing oneself and one's family before others, minding one's own business, and &ndash; for men &ndash; behaving like a [[gentleman]].{{sfn|Gardell|2003|p=289}} In responding to threats and harm, he promoted a policy of ''[[Eye for an eye|lex talionis]]'', for instance reversing a Biblical Christian teaching by stating that \"if a man smite thee on the one cheek, ''smash'' him on the other.\"{{sfn|Gardell|2003|p=289}}\n\nLaVeyan Satanism places great emphasis on the role of [[liberty]] and personal freedom.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=322}} LaVey believed that the ideal Satanist should be individualistic and non-conformist, rejecting what he called the \"colorless existence\" that mainstream society sought to impose on those living within it.{{sfn|Dyrendal|2013|p=129}} He rejected [[consumerism]] and what he called the \"death cult\" of [[fashion]].{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=374}} He praised the human [[Ego (Freudian)|ego]] for encouraging an individual's pride, self-respect, and self-realization and accordingly believed in satisfying the ego's desires.{{sfn|Lap|2013|p=92}} He expressed the view that self-indulgence was a desirable trait,{{sfn|Maxwell-Stuart|2011|p=198}} and that hate and aggression were not wrong or undesirable emotions but that they were necessary and advantageous for survival.{{sfn|Lap|2013|p=94}} Accordingly, he praised the [[Seven Deadly Sins]] as virtues which were beneficial for the individual.{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=288|2a1=Schipper|2y=2010|2p=107}}\n\nSimilarly, LaVey criticized the negative and restrictive attitude to sexuality present in many religions, instead supporting any sexual acts that take place between consenting adults.{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=288|2a1=Lap|2y=2013|2p=91|3a1=Faxneld|3a2=Petersen|3y=2014|3p=168|4a1=van Luijk|4y=2016|4p=321}} His Church welcomed homosexual members from its earliest years,{{sfn|Faxneld|Petersen|2014|p=168}} and he also endorsed celibacy for those who were [[asexuality|asexual]].{{sfn|Faxneld|Petersen|2014|p=168}} He sought to discourage negative feelings of guilt arising from sexual acts such as masturbation and fetishes,{{sfn|Lap|2013|p=91}} and believed that rejecting these sexual inhibitions and guilt would result in a happier and healthier society.{{sfn|Faxneld|Petersen|2014|p=169}} Discussing women, LaVey argued that they should use sex as a tool to manipulate men, in order to advance their own personal power.{{sfn|Faxneld|Petersen|2014|p=170}} Conversely, non-consensual sexual relations, such as [[rape]] and [[child sexual abuse|child molestation]], were denounced by LaVey and his Church.{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=288|2a1=Maxwell-Stuart|2y=2011|2p=198}}\n\nLaVey believed in the imminent demise of Christianity.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=357}} In addition, he believed that society would enter an Age of Satan, in which a generation living in accordance with LaVeyan principles would come to power.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=379}}\nLaVey supported [[eugenics]] and expected it to become a necessity in the future, when it would be used to breed an elite who reflected LaVey's \"Satanic\" principles.{{sfnm|1a1=Lap|1y=2013|1p=95|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=376}} In his view, this elite would be \"superior people\" who displayed the \"Satanic\" qualities of creativity and nonconformity.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=376}} He regarded these traits as capable of hereditary transmission, and made the claim that \"Satanists are born, not made\".{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=376}} He believed that the elite should be siphoned off from the rest of the human \"herd\", with the latter being forced into ghettoes, ideally \"space ghettoes\" located on other planets.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=375}}\nThe anthropologist Jean La Fontaine highlighted an article that appeared in a LaVeyan magazine, ''The Black Flame'', in which one writer described \"a true Satanic society\" as one in which the population consists of \"free-spirited, well-armed, fully-conscious, self-disciplined individuals, who will neither need nor tolerate any external entity 'protecting' them or telling them what they can and cannot do.\"{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=97}} This rebellious approach conflicts with LaVey's firm beliefs in observing the [[rule of law]].{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=97}} Although personally neither a [[fascism|fascist]] nor [[Neo-Nazism|neo-Nazi]],{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=373}} LaVey was on good terms with various neo-Nazi and other right-wing groups operating in the United States.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=368}}\n\n===Magic===\n{{main|Greater and lesser magic}}\n\n[[File:Aleister Crowley.jpg|thumb|right|150px|LaVey's understanding of magic was influenced by the British occultist Aleister Crowley]]\n\nAlthough LaVey's ideas were largely shaped around a secular and scientific world-view, he also expressed a belief in [[magic (paranormal)|magic]].{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2002|1pp=3\u20134|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=336}} Rather than characterising magic as a [[supernatural]] phenomenon, LaVey expressed the view that it was a part of the natural world thus far undiscovered by scientists.{{sfn|Lewis|2002|pp=3\u20134}} Outlined in ''The Satanic Bible'', LaVey defined magic as \"the change in situations or events in accordance with one's will, which would, using normally accepted methods, be unchangeable\",{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1pp=288&ndash;289|2a1=Petersen|2y=2012|2p=95|3a1=Lap|3y=2013|3p=96|4a1=van Luijk|4y=2016|4p=342}} a definition that reflects the influence of the British occultist [[Aleister Crowley]].{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=342}} Although he never explained exactly how he believed that this magical process worked,{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=339}} LaVey stated that magicians could successfully utilise this magical force through intensely imagining their desired goal and thus directing the force of their own willpower toward it.{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2002|1p=4|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=339}} He emphasised the idea that magical forces could be manipulated through \"purely emotional\" rather than intellectual acts.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=339}}\n\nThis practice puts LaVeyan Satanism within a wider tradition of 'high magic' or ceremonial magic,{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=339}} and has also been compared with [[Christian Science]] and [[Scientology]].{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=4}} LaVey adopted beliefs and ideas from older magicians but consciously de-Christianised and Satanised them for his own purposes.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=337}}\nIn presenting himself as applying a scientific perspective on magic, LaVey was likely influenced by Crowley, who had also presented his approach to magic in the same way.{{sfn|Dyrendal|2012|p=376}} However, in contrast to many older ceremonial magicians, LaVey denied that there was any division between [[black magic]] and [[white magic]],{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=289|2a1=Dyrendal|2y=2012|2p=377|3a1=Dyrendal|3a2=Petersen|3a3=Lewis|3y=2016|3p=86}} attributing this dichotomy purely to the \"smug hypocrisy and self-deceit\" of those who called themselves \"white magicians\".{{sfn|Dyrendal|2012|p=377}} He similarly differed from many older magicians who emphasised magic as a practice designed to bring about personal transformation and transcendence; rather, for LaVey magic was employer for material gain, personal influence, to harm enemies, and to gain success in love and sex.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|pp=336\u2013337}}\n\nLaVey defined his system of magic as [[greater and lesser magic]].{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=289|2a1=Petersen|2y=2012|2pp=95\u201396|3a1=Lap|3y=2013|3p=97|4a1=Dyrendal|4a2=Lewis|4a3=Petersen|4y=2016|4p=86}} Greater magic is a form of ritual practice and is meant as psychodramatic catharsis to focus one's emotional energy for a specific purpose. These rites are based on three major psycho-emotive themes: ''compassion'' ([[love]]), ''destruction'' (hate), and ''sex'' (lust).{{sfn|Dyrendal|Lewis|Petersen|2016|p=86}} The space in which a ritual is performed is known as an \"intellectual decompression chamber\",{{sfn|The Invention of Satanism Dyrendal, Petersen|2016|page=89}} where skepticism and disbelief are willfully suspended, thus allowing the magicians to fully express their mental and emotional needs, holding back nothing regarding their deepest feelings and desires. This magic could then be employed to ensure sexual gratification, material gain, personal success, or to curse one's enemies.{{sfn|Gardell|2003|p=289}} LaVey also wrote of \"the balance factor\", insisting that any magical aims should be realistic.{{sfn|Lap|2013|p=98}} These rituals are often considered to be magical acts,{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=98}} with LaVey's Satanism encouraging the practice of [[Magic (paranormal)|magic]] to aid one's selfish ends.{{sfn|Medway|2001|p=21}} Much of Satanic ritual is designed for an individual to carry out alone; this is because concentration is seen as key to performing magical acts.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|pp=98\u201399}}\n\nLesser magic, also referred to an \"everyday\" or \"situational\" magic, is the practice of manipulation by means of applied psychology. LaVey defined it as \"wile and guile obtained through various devices and contrived situations, which when utilized, can create change in accordance with one's will.\"{{sfn|Witchcraft and Magic in Europe, Volume 6: The Twentieth Century|Blecourt, Hutton, Fontaine|1999|p=91}} LaVey wrote that a key concept in lesser magic is the \u201ccommand to look\u201d, which can be accomplished by utilizing elements of \u201csex, sentiment, and wonder\u201d,{{sfn|Controversial New Religions|Lewis, Petersen|p=418}} in addition to the utilization of looks, body language, scents,{{sfn|The Devil's Party: Satanism in Modernity|Faxneld, Petersen|2013|page=97}} color, patterns, and odor.{{sfn|Handbook of Religion and the Authority of Science|Lewis, Hammer|2014|p=90}} This system encourages a form of manipulative role-play, wherein the practitioner may alter several elements of their physical appearance in order to aid them in seducing or \"bewitching\" on object of desire.{{sfn|The Devil's Party: Satanism in Modernity|Faxneld, Petersen|2013|p=97}}\n\nLaVey developed \u201cThe Synthesizer Clock\u201d, the purpose of which is to divide humans into distinct groups of people based primarily on body shape and personality traits.{{sfn|The Devil's Party: Satanism in Modernity|Faxneld, Petersen|2013|p=97}} The synthesizer is modeled as a clock, and based on concepts of [[somatotypes]].{{sfn|Handbook of Religion and the Authority of Science|Petersen|2010|p=67}} The clock is intended to aid a witch in identifying themselves, subsequently aiding in utilizing the \u201cattraction of opposites\u201d to \u201cspellbind\u201d the witch's object of desire by assuming the opposite role.{{sfn|The Devil's Party: Satanism in Modernity|Faxneld, Petersen|2013|p=97}} The successful application of lesser magic is said to be built upon one's understanding of their place on the clock.{{sfn|Sexuality and New Religious Movements|Lewis, Bogdan|2014|p=}} Upon finding your position on the clock, you are encouraged to adapt it as seen fit, and perfect your type by harmonizing its element for better success.{{sfn|The Devil's Party: Satanism in Modernity|Faxneld, Petersen|2013|p=97}} Dyrendal referred to LaVey's techniques as \u201c[[Erving Goffman]] meets [[William Mortensen]]\u201d.{{sfn|Controversial New Religions|Lewis, Petersen|2014|page=418}} Drawing insights from psychology, biology, and sociology,{{sfn|Handbook of Religion and the Authority of Science|Lewis, Hammer|2010|p=89}} Petersen noted that lesser magic combines occult and \u201crejected sciences of body analysis [and] temperaments.\u201d{{sfn|Handbook of Religion and the Authority of Science|Lewis, Hammer|2010|p=68}}\n\n==Basic tenets==\n\nThe \"central convictions\" of LaVeyan Satanism are formulated into three lists, which are regularly reproduced within the Church of Satan's written material.{{sfn|Petersen|2005|p=431}}\n\n===The Nine Satanic Statements===\n[[File:Alchemy sulfur symbol.svg|thumb|right|150px|The [[alchemical symbol]] for [[Sulfur]], as it appears in ''The Satanic Bible'' above the Nine Satanic Statements.]]\n''The Nine Satanic Statements'' are a set of nine assertions made by LaVey in the introductory chapters of ''The Satanic Bible''. They are considered a touchstone of contemporary organized Satanism that constitute, in effect, brief aphorisms that capture Satanic philosophy.{{sfn|Lewis|2001b|p=192}} The first three statements touch on \"indulgence\", \"vital existence\" and \"undefiled wisdom\" which presents a positive view of the Satanist as a carnal, physical and pragmatic being, where enjoyment of physical existence and an undiluted view of this-worldly truth are promoted as the core values of Satanism, combining elements of Darwinism and Epicureanism. Statement four, five and six deal in matters of ethics, through \"kindness to those who deserve it\", \"vengeance\" and \"responsibility to the responsible\", painting a harsh picture of society and human relations by emphasizing justice rather than love. Statements seven, eight and nine reject the dignity of man, sin and the Christian church. Humans are characterized as \"just another animal\", traditional \"sins\" are promoted as means for gratification, and religion as mere business. The adversarial and [[Antinomy|antinomian]] aspect of Satan takes precedence in support of statements four through nine, with non-conformity being presented as a core ideal.{{sfn|Petersen|2011|pp=159-160}}\n\n# Satan represents [[Pleasure|indulgence]] instead of [[abstinence]].\n# Satan represents [[Self-preservation|vital existence]] instead of [[Delusion|spiritual pipe dreams]].\n# Satan represents [[Perspicacity|undefiled wisdom]] instead of hypocritical [[Self-deception|self-deceit]].\n# Satan represents [[Conditional love|kindness to those who deserve it]], instead of [[Unconditional love|love wasted on ingrates]].\n# Satan represents [[Revenge|vengeance]] instead of [[turning the other cheek]].\n# Satan represents [[Accountability|responsibility to the responsible]] instead of concern for [[Victim playing|psychic vampires]].\n# Satan represents man as just another animal who, because of his \"[[Anthropocentrism|divine spiritual and intellectual development]]\", has become the [[Human\u2013wildlife conflict|most vicious animal of all]].\n# Satan represents all of the [[Seven deadly sins|so-called sins]], as they all lead to physical, mental, or emotional gratification.\n# Satan has been the best friend the [[Christian Church|Church]] has ever had, as he has kept it in business all these years.{{sfnm|1a1=Drury|1y=2003|1pp=191&ndash;192|2a1=Baddeley|2y=2010|2p=71|3a1=Van Luijk|3y=2016|3p=297}}\n\n===The Eleven Satanic Rules of the Earth===\n\n# Do not give opinions or advice unless you are asked.\n# Do not tell your troubles to others unless you are sure they want to hear them.\n# When in another's home, show them respect or else do not go there.\n# If a guest in your home annoys you, treat him cruelly and without mercy.\n# Do not make sexual advances unless you are given the mating signal.\n# Do not take that which does not belong to you unless it is a burden to the other person and they cry out to be relieved.\n# Acknowledge the power of magic if you have employed it successfully to obtain your desires. If you deny the power of magic after having called upon it with success, you will lose all you have obtained.\n# Do not complain about anything to which you need not subject yourself.\n# Do not harm little children.\n# Do not kill non-human animals unless you are attacked or for your food.\n# When walking in open territory, bother no one. If someone bothers you, ask him to stop. If he does not stop, destroy him.{{sfn|Drury|2003|pp=192&ndash;193}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.churchofsatan.com/eleven-rules-of-earth/|title=The Eleven Satanic Rules of the Earth|website=Church of Satan|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n===The Nine Satanic Sins===\n\nThese [[sins]], published by LaVey in 1987, outline characteristics Satanists should avoid:<ref>{{cite web\n| title=The Nine Satanic Sins\n| publisher = Learn Religions\n| url=https://www.learnreligions.com/the-nine-satanic-sins-95782\n| accessdate = May 26, 2019\n| author = Catherine Beyer\n}}</ref>\n\n# Stupidity\n# Pretentiousness \n# [[Solipsism]]\n# Self-deceit\n# Herd Conformity\n# Lack of Perspective\n# Forgetfulness of Past Orthodoxies\n# Counterproductive Pride\n# Lack of Aesthetics\n\n==Rites and practices==\n\n===Rituals and ceremonies===\n\nLaVey emphasized that in his tradition, Satanic rites came in two forms, neither of which were acts of worship; in his terminology, \"rituals\" were intended to bring about change, whereas \"ceremonies\" celebrated a particular occasion.{{sfnm|1a1=La Fontaine|1y=1999|1p=98|2a1=Lap|2y=2013|2p=97}} These rituals were often considered to be magical acts,{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=98}} with LaVey's Satanism encouraging the practice of [[Magic (paranormal)|magic]] to aid one's selfish ends.{{sfn|Medway|2001|p=21}} Much of LaVeyan ritual is designed for an individual to carry out alone; this is because concentration is seen as key to performing magical acts.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|pp=98\u201399}} In ''The Satanic Bible'', LaVey described three types of ritual in his religion: sex rituals designed to attract the desired romantic or sexual partner, compassionate rituals with the intent of helping people (including oneself), and destructive magic which seeks to do harm to others.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=98}} In designing these rituals, LaVey drew upon a variety of older sources, with scholar of Satanism Per Faxneld noting that LaVey \"assembled rituals from a hodgepodge of historical sources, literary as well as esoteric\".{{sfn|Faxneld|2013|p=88}}\n\n[[File:Baphomet.png|thumb|left|[[Eliphas Levi]]'s image of [[Baphomet]] is embraced by LaVeyan Satanists as a symbol of duality, fertility, and the \"powers of darkness\", serving as the namesake of their primary insignia, [[The Sigil of Baphomet]].]]\n\nLaVey described a number of rituals in his book, ''[[The Satanic Rituals]]''; these are \"dramatic performances\" with specific instructions surrounding the clothing to be worn, the music to be used, and the actions to be taken.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=97}} This attention to detail in the design of the rituals was intentional, with their pageantry and theatricality intending to engage the participants' senses and aesthetic sensibilities at various levels and enhancing the participants' willpower for magical ends.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|pp=97, 98}} LaVey prescribed that male participants should wear black robes, while older women should wear black, and other women should dress attractively in order to stimulate sexual feelings among many of the men.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=98}} All participants are instructed to wear amulets of either the upturned pentagram or the image of [[Baphomet]].{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=98}}\n\nAccording to LaVey's instructions, on the altar is to be placed an image of Baphomet. This should be accompanied by various candles, all but one of which are to be black. The lone exception is to be a white candle, used in destructive magic, which is kept to the right of the altar.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=98}} Also to be included are a bell which is rung nine times at the start and end of the ceremony, a chalice made of anything but gold, and which contains an alcoholic drink symbolizing the \"Elixir of Life\", a sword that represents aggression, a model phallus used as an [[aspergillum]], a gong, and parchment on which requests to Satan are to be written before being burned.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=98}} Although alcohol was consumed in the church's rites, [[drunkenness]] was frowned upon and the taking of illicit drugs was forbidden.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=100}}\n\nLaVeyan rituals sometimes include anti-Christian blasphemies, which are intended to have a liberating effect on the participants.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=98}}\nIn some of the rituals, a naked woman serves as the altar; in these cases it is made explicit that the woman's body itself becomes the altar, rather than have her simply lying on an existing altar.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=97}} In contrast to longstanding stereotypes about Satanists, there is no place for sexual orgies in LaVeyan ritual.{{sfnm|1a1=La Fontaine|1y=1999|1p=97|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=337}} Neither animal nor human sacrifice takes place.{{sfnm|1a1=La Fontaine|1y=1999|1p=97|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=338}} Children are banned from attending these rituals, with the only exception being the Satanic Baptism, which is specifically designed to involve infants.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=97}}\n\nLaVey also developed his own [[Black Mass]], which was designed as a form of deconditioning to free the participant from any inhibitions that they developed living in Christian society.{{sfnm|1a1=Petersen|1y=2012|1pp=96&ndash;97|2a1=Faxneld|2y=2013|2p=76|3a1=Lap|3y=2013|3p=98}} He noted that in composing the Black Mass rite, he had drawn upon the work of the French fiction writers [[Charles Baudelaire]] and [[Joris-Karl Huysmans]].{{sfn|Faxneld|2013|p=86}} LaVey openly toyed with the use of literature and popular culture in other rituals and ceremonies, thus appealing to artifice, pageantry, and showmanship.{{sfn|Petersen|2012|pp=106&ndash;107}} For instance, he published an outline of a ritual which he termed the \"Call to Cthulhu\" which drew upon the stories of the alien god [[Cthulhu]] authored by American horror writer [[H. P. Lovecraft]]. In this rite, set to take place at night in a secluded location near to a turbulent body of water, a celebrant takes on the role of Cthulhu and appears before the assembled Satanists, signing a pact between them in the language of Lovecraft's fictional \"Old Ones\".{{sfn|Petersen|2012|p=106}}\n\n===Holidays===\n{{main|Satanic holidays}}\n\nLaVey and the Church of Satan deemed an individual's birthday to be the most important day of the year.{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2001b|1p=50|2a1=Gardell|2y=2003|2p=288|3a1=Lap|3y=2013|3p=99|4a1=van Luijk|4y=2016|4p=330}} [[Walpurgisnacht]] (April 30) is celebrated as the date on which LaVey founded his Church.{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2001b|1pp=50&ndash;51|2a1=Gardell|2y=2003|2p=288}} A third annual festival is [[Halloween]], which also has associations with magic and dark entities.{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2001b|1p=51|2a1=Gardell|2y=2003|2p=288}}\n\n===Symbolism===\n[[Image:SamaelLilithGoatPentagram.png|thumb|right|The Sigil of Baphomet]]\nAs a symbol of his Satanic church, LaVey adopted the upturned five-pointed pentagram.{{sfn|Medway|2001|p=26}} The upturned pentagram had previously been used by the French occultist [[Eliphas L\u00e9vi]], and had been adopted by his disciple, [[Stanislas de Guaita]], who merged it with a goat's head in his 1897 book, ''Key of Black Magic''.{{sfn|Medway|2001|p=26}} In the literature and imagery predating LaVey, imagery used to represent the \"satanic\" is denoted by inverted crosses and blasphemous parodies of Christian art. The familiar goat's head inside an inverted pentagram did not become the foremost symbol of Satanism until the founding of the Church of Satan in 1966.{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=20}} LaVey learned of this variant of the symbol after it had been reproduced on the front cover of Maurice Bessy's [[coffee table book]], ''Pictorial History of Magic and the Supernatural''.{{sfnm|1a1=Medway|1y=2001|1p=26|2a1=Lewis|2y=2001b|2p=20}} Feeling that this symbol embodied his philosophy, LaVey decided to adopt it for his Church.{{sfn|Lewis|2001b|p=20}} In its formative years, the church utilized this image on its membership cards, stationary, medallions and most notably above the altar in the ritual chamber of the Black House.{{sfn|Lewis|2001b|p=21}}\n\nDuring the writing of ''The Satanic Bible'', it was decided that a unique version of the symbol should be rendered to be identified exclusively with the church. LaVey created a new version of Guaita's image, one which was geometrically precise, with two perfect circles surrounding the pentagram, the goat head redrawn, and the Hebrew lettering altered to look more serpentine.{{sfn|Lewis|2001b|p=21}} LaVey had this design copyrighted to the church,{{sfn|Lewis|2001b|p=21}} claiming authorship under the pseudonym of \"Hugo Zorilla\".{{sfn|Partridge|2005|p=376}} In doing so, the symbol &ndash; which came to be known as the [[Sigil of Baphomet]]{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2001b|1p=20|2a1=Partridge|2y=2005|2p=376}} &ndash; came to be closely associated with Satanism in the public imagination.{{sfn|Lewis|2001b|p=20}}\n\n==History==\n\n===Origins: 1966\u201372===\nAlthough there were forms of religious Satanism that predated the creation of LaVeyan Satanism\u2014namely those propounded by [[Stanis\u0142aw Przybyszewski]] and [[Ben Kadosh]]\u2014these had no unbroken lineage of succession to LaVey's form.{{sfn|Faxneld|2013|p=75}} For this reason, the sociologist of religion [[Massimo Introvigne]] stated that \"with few exceptions, LaVey is at the origins of all contemporary Satanism\".{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=299}} Similarly, the historian Ruben van Luijk claimed that the creation of LaVeyan Satanism marked \"the actual beginning of Satanism as a religion such as it is practiced in the world today\".{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=297}}\n\nAfter he came to public attention, LaVey shielded much of his early life in secrecy, and little is known about it for certain.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=295}} He had been born in [[Chicago]] as Howard Stanton Levey in either March or April 1930.{{sfnm|1a1=Dyrendal|1a2=Lewis|1a3=Petersen|1y=2016|1p=51|2a1=Introvigne|2y=2016|2p=300}} He was of mixed Ukrainian, Russian, and German ancestry.{{sfn|Dyrendal|Lewis|Petersen|2016|p=51}} He claimed to have worked in the [[circus]] and [[carnival]] in the years following the [[Second World War]],{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=301}} and in later years, he also alleged that he worked at the San Francisco Orchestra, although this never existed.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=301}} He also claimed to have had a relationship with a young [[Marilyn Monroe]], although this too was untrue.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|pp=300\u2013301}}\n\nBy the 1960s he was living at 6114 California Street in San Francisco, a house that he had inherited from his parents.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|pp=294, 296}} He took an interest in occultism and amassed a large collection of books on the subject.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=296}} At some point between 1957 and 1960 he began hosting classes at his house every Friday in which lectures on occultism and other subjects were given.{{sfn|Dyrendal|Lewis|Petersen|2016|p=52}} Among the topics covered were [[freak]]s, [[extra-sensory perception]], [[Spiritualism]], [[cannibalism]], and historical methods of [[torture]].{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=296}} An informal group established around these lectures, which came to be known as the Magic Circle.{{sfnm|1a1=Dyrendal|1a2=Lewis|1a3=Petersen|1y=2016|1p=52|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=296}} Among those affiliated with this gathering were the filmmaker and [[Thelema|Thelemite]] occultist [[Kenneth Anger]],{{sfn|Dyrendal|Lewis|Petersen|2016|p=53}} and the anthropologist [[Michael Harner]], who later established the [[core shamanism]] movement.{{sfn|Dyrendal|Lewis|Petersen|2016|p=53}}\n\nLaVey likely began preparations for the formation of his [[Church of Satan]] in either 1965 or early 1966,{{sfn|Dyrendal|Lewis|Petersen|2016|p=52}} and it was officially founded on [[Walpurgisnacht]] 1966.{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2002|1p=5|2a1=Gardell|2y=2003|2p=285|3a1=Baddeley|3y=2010|3p=71|4a1=Dyrendal|4a2=Lewis|4a3=Petersen|4y=2016|4p=52}} He then declared that 1966 marked Year One of the new Satanic era.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=297}} It was the first organized church in modern times to be devoted to the figure of Satan,{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=5}} and according to Faxneld and Petersen, the church represented \"the first public, highly visible, and long-lasting organisation which propounded a coherent satanic discourse\".{{sfn|Faxneld|Petersen|2013|p=81}} Its early members were the attendees of LaVey's Magic Circle, although it soon began attracting new recruits.{{sfn|Dyrendal|Lewis|Petersen|2016|p=53}} Many of these individuals were sadomasochists or homosexuals, attracted by the LaVeyan openness to different sexual practices.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=346}} LaVey had painted his house black,{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=296}} with it becoming known as \"the [[Black House (Church of Satan)|Black House]]\",{{sfnm|1a1=Petersen|1y=2005|1p=428|2a1=Baddeley|2y=2010|2pp=66, 71|3a1=Dyrendal|3a2=Lewis|3a3=Petersen|3y=2016|3p=53}} and it was here that weekly rituals were held every Friday night.{{sfn|Dyrendal|Lewis|Petersen|2016|p=53}}\n\nLaVey played up to his Satanic associations by growing a pointed beard and wearing a black cloak and inverted pentagram.{{sfn|Drury|2003|p=188}} He added to his eccentric persona by obtaining unusual pets, including a lion that was kept caged in his back garden.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=296}} Describing himself as the \"High Priest of Satan\",{{sfn|Drury|2003|p=197}} LaVey defined his position within the church as \"monarchical in nature, papal in degree and absolute in power\".{{sfn|Gardell|2003|p=287}} He led the churches' governing Council of Nine,{{sfn|Gardell|2003|p=287}} and implemented a system of five initiatory levels that the LaVeyan Satanist could advance through by demonstrating their knowledge of LaVeyan philosophy and their personal accomplishments in life.{{sfn|Gardell|2003|p=287}} These were known as Apprentice Satanist I\u00b0, Witch or Warlock II\u00b0, Priest or Priestess of Mendes III\u00b0, Magister IV\u00b0, and Magus V\u00b0.{{sfn|Drury|2003|p=197}}\n\n{{Quote box\n| title = \n| quote = Never one for theory, LaVey created a belief system somewhere between religion, philosophy, psychology, and carnival (or circus), freely appropriating science, mythology, fringe beliefs, and play in a potent mix. The core goal was always indulgence and vital existence, based on the devices and desires of the [[self-made man]].\n| source = \u2014 Per Faxneld and Jesper Petersen.{{sfn|Faxneld|Petersen|2013|p=79}}\n| align = left\n| width = 30em\n| border = 1px\n| fontsize = 85%\n| title_bg = \n| title_fnt = \n| salign = right\n}}\n\nThe church experienced its \"golden age\" from 1966 to 1972, when it had a strong media presence.{{sfn|Petersen|2013|p=136}}  In February 1967, LaVey held a much publicized Satanic wedding, which was followed by the Satanic baptism of his daughter Zeena in May, and then a Satanic funeral in December.{{sfnm|1a1=Petersen|1y=2005|1p=438|2a1=Baddeley|2y=2010|2p=71|3a1=Introvigne|3y=2016|3p=309|4a1=van Luijk|4y=2016|4p=297}} Another publicity-attracting event was the \"Topless Witch Revue\", a nightclub show held on San Francisco's North Beach; the use of topless women to attract attention alienated a number of the church's early members.{{sfnm|1a1=Dyrendal|1a2=Lewis|1a3=Petersen|1y=2016|1p=54|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=346}} Through these and other activities, he soon attracted international media attention, being dubbed \"the Black Pope\".{{sfn|Baddeley|2010|p=71}} He also attracted a number of celebrities to join his Church, most notably [[Sammy Davis Junior]] and [[Jayne Mansfield]].{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=286|2a1=Baddeley|2y=2010|2p=72|3a1=Schipper|3y=2010|3pp=105&ndash;106}} LaVey also established branches of the church, known as ''grottos'', in various parts of the United States.{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=287|2a1=Baddeley|2y=2010|2p=74}} He may have chosen the term ''grotto'' over ''[[coven]]'' because the latter term had come to be used by practitioners of the modern Pagan religion of [[Wicca]].{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=344}} These included the Babylon Grotto in [[Detroit]], the Stygian Grotto in [[Dayton]], and the Lilith Grotto in [[New York City]].{{sfn|Baddeley|2010|p=74}} In 1971, a Dutch follower of LaVey's, Maarten Lamers, established his own Kerk van Satan grotto in [[Amsterdam]].{{sfnm|1a1=Introvigne|1y=2016|1p=519|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2pp=344\u2013345}}\n\nAs a result of the success of the film ''[[Rosemary's Baby (film)|Rosemary's Baby]]'' and the concomitant growth of interest in Satanism, an editor at [[Avon Books]], Peter Mayer, approached LaVey and commissioned him to write a book, which became ''[[The Satanic Bible]]''.{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2002|1p=8|2a1=Baddeley|2y=2010|2p=72}} While part of the text was LaVey's original writing, other sections of the book consisted of direct quotations from [[Arthur Desmond]]'s right-wing tract ''[[Might is Right]]'' and the occultist [[Aleister Crowley]]'s version of [[John Dee]]'s ''Enochian Keys''.{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2002|1p=8|2a1=Introvigne|2y=2016|2p=315}} There is evidence that LaVey was inspired by the writings of the American philosopher [[Ayn Rand]]; and while accusations that he plagiarized her work in ''The Satanic Bible'' have been denied by one author, {{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=9}} Chris Mathews stated that \"LaVey stole selectively and edited lightly\" and that his \"Satanism at times closely parallels Ayn Rand's [[Objectivism (Ayn Rand)|Objectivist philosophy]].\"{{sfn|Mathews|2009|p=65-66}} The book ''The Satanic Bible'' served to present LaVey's ideas to a far wider audience than they had previously had.{{sfn|Baddeley|2010|p=72}} In 1972, he published a sequel, ''The Satanic Rituals''.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=298}}\n\nLaVey's Church emerged at a point in American history when Christianity was on the decline as many of the nation's youth broke away from their parental faith and explored alternative systems of religiosity.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=298}} The milieu in which LaVey's Church was operating was dominated by the [[counterculture of the 1960s]]; his Church reflected some of its concerns &ndash; free love, alternative religions, freedom from church and state &ndash; but ran contrary to some of the counterculture's other main themes, such as peace and love, compassion, and the use of mind-altering drugs.{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=295|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=298}} He expressed condemnation of the [[hippies]]; in one ritual he hung an image of [[Timothy Leary]] upside down while stamping on a tablet of [[LSD]].{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=299}}\n\n===Later development: 1972&ndash;present===\n\n[[File:Karla LaVey.jpg|right|thumb|Karla LaVey, founder of the First Satanic Church, in 2012]]\n\nLaVey ceased conducting group rituals and workshops in his home in 1972.{{sfnm|1a1=Lap|1y=2013|1p=84|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=345}}\nIn 1973, church leaders in Michigan, Ohio, and Florida split to form their own Church of Satanic Brotherhood, however this disbanded in 1974 when one of its founders publicly converted to Christianity.{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=7}} Subsequently, Church members based in Kentucky and Indiana left to found the [[Ordo Templi Satanis]].{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=7}} In 1975, LaVey disbanded all grottos, leaving the organisation as a membership-based group that existed largely on paper.{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2002|1p=7|2a1=Lap|2y=2013|2p=84|3a1=Introvigne|3y=2016|3p=518}} He claimed that this had been necessary because the grottos had come to be dominated by social misfits who had not benefitted the church as a whole.{{sfn|Gardell|2003|p=287}} In a private letter, he expressed frustration that despite growing church membership, \"brain surgeons and Congressmen are still in short supply\".{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|pp=346\u2013347}} He also announced that thenceforth all higher degrees in the church would be awarded in exchange for contributions of cash, real estate, or valuable art.{{sfnm|1a1=Drury|1y=2003|1p=193|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=347}} Dissatisfied with these actions, in 1975, the high-ranking Church member Michael Aquino left to found his own Satanic organisation, the [[Temple of Set]],{{sfnm|1a1=Drury|1y=2003|1pp=193&ndash;194|2a1=Gallagher|2y=2006|2p=160|3a1=Schipper|3y=2010|3p=105}} which differed from LaVey's Church by adopting a belief that Satan literally existed.{{sfn|Schipper|2010|p=109}} According to Lap, from this point on Satanism became a \"splintered and disorganized movement\".{{sfn|Lap|2013|p=84}}\n\nBetween the abolition of the grotto system in 1975 and the establishment of the [[internet]] in the mid-1990s, ''The Satanic Bible'' remained the primary means of propagating Satanism.{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=2}} During this period, a decentralized, anarchistic movement of Satanists developed that was shaped by many of the central themes that had pervaded LaVey's thought and which was expressed in ''The Satanic Bible''.{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=4}} Lewis argued that in this community, ''The Satanic Bible'' served as a \"quasi-scripture\" because these independent Satanists were able to adopt certain ideas from the book while merging them with ideas and practices drawn from elsewhere.{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=4}}\n\nDuring the late 1980s, LaVey returned to the limelight, giving media interviews, attracting further celebrities, and reinstating the grotto system.{{sfn|Gardell|2003|p=287}} In 1984 he separated from his wife, Diane Hegarty, and began a relationship with Blanche Barton,{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|pp=512\u2013513}} who was his personal assistant.{{sfn|Lewis|2001b|p=51}} In 1988 Hegarty brought a court case against LaVey, claiming that he she owned half of the church and LaVey's Black House. The court found in Hegarty's favour, after which LaVey immediately declared bankruptcy.{{sfnm|1a1=Introvigne|1y=2016|1p=516|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2pp=377\u2013378}} In May 1992, the ex-couple reached a settlement. The Black House was sold to a wealthy friend, the property developer Donald Werby, who agreed to allow LaVey to continue living at the residence for free.{{sfnm|1a1=Introvigne|1y=2016|1p=516|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=378}} Also in 1992, LaVey published his first book in twenty years, ''The Devil's Notebook''.{{sfn|Gardell|2003|p=287}} This was followed by the posthumous ''Satan Speaks'' in 1998, which included a foreword from the rock singer [[Marilyn Manson]],{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=287|2a1=Introvigne|2y=2016|2p=516}} who was a priest in the church.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=384}}\n\nIn his final years, LaVey suffered from a heart condition, displayed increasing paranoia, and died in October 1997.{{sfnm|1a1=Introvigne|1y=2016|2p=516|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2pp=378\u2013379}} In November, the church announced that it would subsequently be run by two High Priestesses of joint rank, Barton and LaVey's daughter [[Karla LaVey]].{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=516}} That same year, the church established an official website.{{sfn|Petersen|2013|p=140}} Barton attempted to purchase the Black House from Werby, but was unable to raise sufficient funds; the building had fallen into disrepair and was demolished in 2001, subsequently being replaced with an apartment block.{{sfnm|1a1=Introvigne|1y=2016|1p=516|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=380}} A disagreement subsequently emerged between Barton and Karla, resulting in an agreement that Barton would retain legal ownership of the name and organization of the church while LaVey's personal belongings and copyrights would be distributed among his three children, Karla, Zeena, and Satan Xerxes.{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=287|2a1=Introvigne|2y=2016|2pp=516\u2013517}} Barton stood down as High Priestess in 2002, although continued to chair the church's Council of Nine.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=517}} The headquarters of the church were then moved from San Francisco to New York, where [[Peter H. Gilmore]] was appointed the church's High Priest, and his wife Peggy Nadramia as its High Priestess.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=517}}\n\n[[File:Peter H Gilmore 2 by David Shankbone.jpg|thumb|left|Peter Gilmore, High Priest of the Church of Satan]]\n\nAfter LaVey's death, conflict over the nature of Satanism intensified within the Satanic community.{{sfn|Petersen|2013|p=139}} At Halloween 1999 Karla established the [[First Satanic Church]], which uses its website to promote the idea that it represents a direct continuation of the original Church of Satan as founded by Anton LaVey.{{sfnm|1a1=Gallagher|1y=2006|1p=162|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=380}} Other LaVeyan groups appeared elsewhere in the United States. An early member of the Church of Satan, John Dewey Allee, established his own First Church of Satan, claiming allegiance to LaVey's original teachings and professing that LaVey himself had deviated from them in later life.{{sfn|Gallagher|2006|p=162}} In 1986, Paul Douglas Valentine founded the New York City-based [[World Church of Satanic Liberation]], having recruited many of its members through [[Herman Slater]]'s Magickal Childe esoteric store. Its membership remained small and it was discontinued in 2011.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=517}} In 1991, the Embassy of Lucifer was established by the Canadian [[Tsirk Susuej]], which was influenced by LaVeyan teachings but held that Satan was a real entity.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=518}} Splinter groups from Susuej's organisation included the Embassy of Satan in [[Stewart, British Columbia]], and the Luciferian Light Group in [[Baltimore]].{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=518}}\n\nLaVeyan groups also cropped up elsewhere in the world, with a particular concentration in Scandinavia; most of these Scandinavian groups either split from the Church of Satan or never affiliated with it.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=520}} These included the Svenska Satanistkyrkan and the Det Norske Sataniske Samfunn,{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=520}} as well as the Prometheus Grotten of the Church of Satan which was established in Denmark in 1997 but which officially seceded in 2000.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=520}} A Satanic Church was also established in [[Estonia]] based on the LaVeyan model; it later renamed itself the [[Order of the Black Widow]].{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|pp=519\u2013520}}\n\nThe Church of Satan became increasingly doctrinally-rigid and focused on maintaining the purity of LaVeyan Satanism.{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2002|1p=5|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=380}} The church's increased emphasis on their role as the bearer of LaVey's legacy was partly a response to the growth in non-LaVeyan Satanists.{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=5}} Some Church members &ndash; including Gilmore{{sfn|Petersen|2013|p=140}} &ndash; claimed that only they were the \"real\" Satanists and that those belonging to different Satanic traditions were \"pseudo\" Satanists.{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2002|1p=5|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=380}} After examining many of these claims on the church's website, Lewis concluded that it was \"''obsessed'' with shoring up its own legitimacy by attacking the heretics, especially those who criticize LaVey\".{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=7}} Meanwhile, the church experienced an exodus of its membership in the 2000s, with many of these individuals establishing new groups online.{{sfn|Petersen|2013|p=139}} Although the church's public face had performed little ceremonial activity since the early 1970s, in June 2006 they held a Satanic 'High Mass' in Los Angeles to mark the church's fortieth birthday.{{sfn|Petersen|2012|pp=115&ndash;116}}\n\n==Demographics==\n\nMembership levels of the Church of Satan are hard to determine, as the organisation has not released such information.{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=287|2a1=Petersen|2y=2005|2p=430}} During its early years, the church claimed a membership of around 10,000, although defectors subsequently claimed that the number was only in the hundreds.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=344}} Membership was largely, although not exclusively, white.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|pp=369\u2013370}} LaVey recognised this, suggesting that the church appealed particularly to white Americans because they lacked the strong sense of ethnic identity displayed by African-Americans and Hispanic Americans.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=370}} The historian of religion [[Massimo Introvigne]] suggested that it had never had more than 1000 or 2000 members at its height, but that LaVeyan ideas had had a far greater influence through LaVey's books.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=320}} Membership is gained by paying $225 and filling out a registration statement,{{sfn|Petersen|2005|p=430}} and thus initiates are bestowed with lifetime memberships and not charged annual fees.{{sfn|Gardell|2003|p=287}}\n\nLa Fontaine thought it likely that the easy availability of LaVey's writings would have encouraged the creation of various Satanic groups that were independent of the Church of Satan itself.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=100}} In ''The Black Flame'', a number of groups affiliated with the church have been mentioned, most of which are based in the United States and Canada although two groups were cited as having existed in New Zealand.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=100}} In his 2001 examination of Satanists, the sociologist [[James R. Lewis (scholar)|James R. Lewis]] noted that, to his surprise, his findings \"consistently pointed to the centrality of LaVey's influence on modern Satanism\".{{sfn|Lewis|2001a|p=5}} \"Reflecting the dominant influence of Anton LaVey's thought\", Lewis noted that the majority of those whom he examined were atheists or agnostics, with 60% of respondents viewing Satanism as a symbol rather than a real entity.{{sfn|Lewis|2001a|p=11}} 20% of his respondents described ''The Satanic Bible'' as the most important factor that attracted them to Satanism.{{sfn|Lewis|2001a|p=15}} Elsewhere, Lewis noted that few Satanists who weren't members of the Church of Satan would regard themselves as \"orthodox LaVeyans\".{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=2}}\n \nExamining the number of LaVeyan Satanists in Britain, in 1995 the religious studies scholar Graham Harvey noted that the Church of Satan had no organized presence in the country.{{sfn|Harvey|1995|p=290}} He noted that LaVey's writings were widely accessible in British bookshops,{{sfn|Harvey|1995|p=290}} and La Fontaine suggested that there may have been individual Church members within the country.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=100}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal bar|Religion|Philosophy}}\n*{{annotated link|Contemporary Religious Satanism|''Contemporary Religious Satanism''}}\n*{{annotated link|Satanic ritual abuse}}\n*{{annotated link|Devil in popular culture}}\n*{{annotated link|Conceptions of God}}\n*{{annotated link|Nontheistic religions}}\n*{{annotated link|Religious naturalism}}\n*{{annotated link|Secular religion}}\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{Refbegin|30em|indent=yes}}\n* {{cite contribution |last=Alfred |first=A. |contribution=The Church of Satan |title=The New Religious Consciousness |editor=C. Glock |editor2=R. Bellah|location=Berkeley |pages=180&ndash;202 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title=Lucifer Rising: Sin, Devil Worship & Rock n' Roll |last=Baddeley |first=Gavin |location=London |publisher=Plexus |year=2010 |edition=third |isbn=978-0-85965-455-5 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite encyclopedia |last=Bromley |first=David G. |authorlink=David G. Bromley |editor=Lindsay Jones |encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Religion |title=Satanism |edition=2 |year=2005 |publisher=Macmillan Reference USA |volume=12 |location=Detroit, IL|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Cavaglion |first1=Gabriel |last2=Sela-Shayovitz |first2=Revital |title=The Cultural Construction of Contemporary Satanic Legends in Israel |journal=Folklore |date=2005 |volume=116 |issue=3 |pages=255\u2013271 |doi=10.1080/00155870500282701 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Drury |first=Nevill |year=2003 |title=Magic and Witchcraft: From Shamanism to the Technopagans |location=London |publisher=Thames and Hudson |isbn=978-0500511404 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite contribution|contribution=Satan and the Beast: The Influence of Aleister Crowley on Modern Satanism |last=Dyrendal |first=Asbj\u00f8rn |year=2012 |title=Aleister Crowley and Western Esotericism |editor=Bogdan, Henrik |editor2=Starr, Martin P. |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford and New York |isbn=978-0-19-986309-9 |pages=369\u2013394 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite contribution |last=Dyrendal |first=Asbj\u00f8rn |author1-mask={{long dash}} |contribution=Hidden Persuaders and Invisible Wars: Anton LaVey and Conspiracy Culture |title=The Devil's Party: Satanism in Modernity |editor=Per Faxneld |editor2=Jesper Aagaard Petersen|publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford |year=2013 |isbn=978-0-19-977924-6 |pages=123\u201340 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Dyrendal |first1=Asbj\u00f8rn |last2=Lewis |first2=James R. |last3=Petersen |first3=Jesper Aa. |year=2016 |title=The Invention of Satanism |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford and New York |isbn=978-0195181104 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite contribution |last=Faxneld |first=Per |contribution=Secret Lineages and de facto Satanists: Anton LaVey's Use of Esoteric Tradition |title=Contemporary Esotericism |editor=Egil Asprem |editor2=Kennet Granholm|publisher=Equinox |location=Sheffield |year=2013 |pages=72&ndash;90 |isbn=978-1-908049-32-2 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite contribution |last1=Faxneld |first1=Per |last2=Petersen |first2=Jesper Aa. |contribution=The Black Pope and the Church of Satan |title=The Devil's Party: Satanism in Modernity |editor=Per Faxneld |editor2=Jesper Aagaard Petersen|publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford |year=2013 |isbn=978-0-19-977924-6 |pages=79\u201382 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite contribution |last1=Faxneld |first1=Per |last2=Petersen |first2=Jesper Aagaard |author1-mask={{long dash}} |author2-mask={{long dash}} |contribution=Cult of Carnality: Sexuality, Eroticism, and Gender in Contemporary Satanism |title=Sexuality and New Religious Movements |editor=Henrik Bogdan |editor2=James R. Lewis|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |location=New York |year=2014 |isbn=978-1137409621 |pages=165\u2013181 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite encyclopedia |last=Gallagher |first=Eugene V. |authorlink=Eugene V. Gallagher |editor=Lindsay Jones |encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Religion |title=New Religious Movements: Scriptures of New Religious Movements |edition=2 |year=2005 |publisher=Macmillan Reference USA |volume=12 |location=Detroit, IL|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite contribution |last=Gallagher |first=Eugene |contribution=Satanism and the Church of Satan |title=Introduction to New and Alternative Religions in America |editor=Eugene V. Gallagher |editor2=W. Michael Ashcraft|year=2006 |pages=151&ndash;168 |location= |publisher=Greenwood |isbn=978-0313050787 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book| last=Gardell |first=Matthias |title=Gods of the Blood: The Pagan Revival and White Separatism |year=2003 |publisher=Duke University Press |location=Durham and London |isbn=978-0-8223-3071-4 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Harvey |first=Graham |title=Satanism in Britain Today |journal=Journal of Contemporary Religion |volume=10 |issue=3 |year=1995 |pages=283&ndash;296 |doi=10.1080/13537909508580747 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Introvigne |first=Massimo |title=Satanism: A Social History |year=2016 |location=Leiden and Boston |publisher=Brill |isbn=978-9004288287 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite contribution |last=La Fontaine |first=Jean |contribution=Satanism and Satanic Mythology |title=The Athlone History of Witchcraft and Magic in Europe Volume 6: The Twentieth Century |editor=Bengt Ankarloo |editor2=Stuart Clark|publisher=Athlone |location=London |year=1999 |isbn=0 485 89006 2 |pages=94&ndash;140 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite contribution |last=Lap |first=Amina Olander |contribution=Categorizing Modern Satanism: An Analysis of LaVey's Early Writings |title=The Devil's Party: Satanism in Modernity |editor=Per Faxneld |editor2=Jesper Aagaard Petersen|publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford |year=2013 |isbn=978-0-19-977924-6 |pages=83\u2013102 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Lewis |first=James L. |title=Who Serves Satan? A Demographic and Ideological Profile |journal=Marburg Journal of Religion |volume=6 |number=2 |year=2001a |pages=1&ndash;25 |url=https://www.uni-marburg.de/fb03/ivk/mjr/pdfs/2001/articles/lewis2001.pdf |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Lewis |first=James L. |author1-mask={{long dash}} |title=Satanism Today: An Encyclopedia of Religion, Folklore, and Popular Culture |publisher=ABC-Clio |location=Santa Barbara |year=2001b |isbn=978-1576072929 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Lewis |first=James L. |author1-mask={{long dash}} |title=Diabolical Authority: Anton LaVey, ''The Satanic Bible'' and the Satanist \"Tradition\" |journal=Marburg Journal of Religion |volume=7 |number=1 |year=2002 |pages=1&ndash;16 |url=https://www.uni-marburg.de/fb03/ivk/mjr/pdfs/2002/articles/lewis2002.pdf |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Lewis |first=James R. |author1-mask={{long dash}} |title=Legitimating New Religions |year=2003 |publisher=Rutgers University Press |location=New Brunswick, NJ |isbn=978-0-8135-3534-0 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Mathews|first=Chris|title=Modern Satanism: Anatomy of a Radical Subculture|publisher=[[Greenwood Publishing Group|Praeger Publishers]]|year=2009|isbn=978-0313366390|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Maxwell-Stuart |first=P. G. |title=Satan: A Biography |publisher=Amberley |location=Stroud |year=2011 |isbn=978-1-4456-0575-3 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Medway |first=Gareth J. |title=Lure of the Sinister: The Unnatural History of Satanism |publisher=New York University Press |location=New York and London |year=2001 |isbn=9780814756454 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite encyclopedia |last=Muzzatti |first=Stephen L. |editor=Mary Bosworth|encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Prisons and Correctional Facilities |title=Satanism |year=2005 |publisher=Sage Reference |volume=2 |location=Thousand Oaks, CA |id= |isbn=978-1-4129-2535-8 |oclc= |doi= |pages=874\u2013876|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Partridge |first=Christopher |year=2004 |title=The Re-Enchantment of the West Volume. 1: Alternative Spiritualities, Sacralization, Popular Culture, and Occulture |publisher=T&T Clark International |location=London |isbn=978-0567084088 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Partridge |first=Christopher |author1-mask={{long dash}} |title=The Re-Enchantment of the West, Volume 2: Alternative Spiritualities, Sacralization, Popular Culture and Occulture |year=2005 |location=London |publisher=T&T Clark |isbn= |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite contribution |last=Petersen |first=Jesper Aagaard |contribution=Modern Satanism: Dark Doctrines and Black Flames |title=Controversial New Religions |editor=James R. Lewis |editor2=Jesper Aagaard Petersen |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford |year=2005 |isbn=978-0195156836 |pages=423&ndash;457 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite contribution |last=Petersen |first=Jesper Aagaard |author1-mask={{long dash}} |contribution=Satanists and Nuts: The Role of Schisms in Modern Satanism |title=Sacred Schisms: How Religions Divide |editor=James R. Lewis |editor2=Sarah M. Lewis |year=2009 |pages=218&ndash;247 |location=Cambridge |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0521881470 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite contribution |last=Petersen |first=Jesper Aagaard |author1-mask={{long dash}} |contribution=\"We Demand Bedrock Knowledge\": Modern Satanism Between Secularized Esotericism and 'Esotericized' Secularism |title=Handbook of Religion and the Authority of Science |editor=James R. Lewis |editor2=Olav Hammer|publisher=Brill |location=Leiden |year=2010 |pages=67&ndash;114 |isbn=978-9004187917 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite thesis |last=Petersen |first=Jesper Aagaard |author1-mask={{long dash}} |title=Between Darwin and the Devil: Modern Satanism as Discourse, Milieu and Self |year=2011 |type=Doctoral thesis |publisher=Norwegian University of Science and Technology |url=http://ntnu.diva-portal.org/smash/get/diva2:455597/FULLTEXT02.pdf |ref=harv |accessdate=2016-03-20 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401221914/http://ntnu.diva-portal.org/smash/get/diva2:455597/FULLTEXT02.pdf |archivedate=2016-04-01 |url-status=dead }}\n* {{cite journal |last=Petersen |first=Jesper Aagaard |author1-mask={{long dash}} |title=The Seeds of Satan: Conceptions of Magic in Contemporary Satanism |journal=Aries: Journal for the Study of Western Esotericism |volume=12 |number=1 |year=2012 |pages=91&ndash;129 |doi=10.1163/147783512X614849 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite contribution |last=Petersen |first=Jesper Aagaard |author1-mask={{long dash}} |contribution=From Book to Bit: Enacting Satanism Online |title=Contemporary Esotericism |editor=Egil Asprem |editor2=Kennet Granholm|publisher=Acumen |location=Durham |year=2013 |pages=134&ndash;158 |isbn=978-1-908049-32-2 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite contribution |last=Petersen |first=Jesper Aagaard |author1-mask={{long dash}} |contribution=Carnal, Chthonian, Complicated: The Matter of Modern Satanism |title=Controversial New Religions |edition=second |editor=James R. Lewis |editor2=Jesper Aagaard Petersen |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford |year=2014 |pages=399&ndash;434 |isbn=978-0199315314 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Schipper |first=Bernd U. |title=From Milton to Modern Satanism: The History of the Devil and the Dynamics between Religion and Literature |journal=Journal of Religion in Europe |volume=3 |issue=1 |year=2010 |pages=103&ndash;124 |doi=10.1163/187489210X12597396698744  |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Taub|first1=Diane E.|last2=Nelson|first2=Lawrence D.|title=Satanism in Contemporary America: Establishment or Underground?|journal=The Sociological Quarterly|date=August 1993|volume=34|issue=3|pages=523\u2013541|ref=harv|doi=10.1111/j.1533-8525.1993.tb00124.x}}\n* {{cite book |first=Ruben |last=van Luijk |year=2016 |title=Children of Lucifer: The Origins of Modern Religious Satanism |location=Oxford |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780190275105 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Wright|first=Lawrence|title=Saints & Sinners|year=1993|publisher=Alfred A. Knopf, Inc|location=New York|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1bwDrFdnNcsC|isbn=0-394-57924-0|authorlink=Lawrence Wright|ref=harv}}\n\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.churchofsatan.com/ Official Church of Satan website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120725045139/http://www.underworldamusements.net/blog/2011/satanism-as-weltanschauung/ \u201cSatanism as Weltanschauung\u201d, the philosophy of the Church of Satan (presented by Kevin I. Slaughter at the Maryland Institute College of Art)]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=T5fxA6yhwTY/ \"Satan as Rebel Hero: Henry M. Tichenor and the Radical Anti-religious (presented by Kevin I. Slaughter and Robert Merciless at SkeptiCamp DC on October 3, 2010, College Park, MD)]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BzlOtvDFjx0/ \"What Does Satanism Mean to You?\" (Interview with members of the Church of Satan)]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7uiJsAp82jg/ \"Inside the Church of Satan (Documentary)]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kkmuV5R_O6g/ 9sense Podcast interview with Peter H. Gilmore on Walpurgisnacht.]\n*{{wikinews-inline|Satanism: An interview with Church of Satan High Priest Peter Gilmore}}\n\n{{LaVeyan Satanism}}\n{{Greater and Lesser Magic}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Laveyan Satanism}}\n[[Category:Satanism| ]]\n[[Category:Church of Satan]]\n[[Category:New religious movements]]\n[[Category:Philosophical movements]]\n[[Category:Self religions]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Atheistic religion founded by Anton LaVey, in which Satan is a symbol of human freedom, but not believed to be a separately existing supernatural being}}\n[[File:Baphosimb.svg|thumb|right|The Sigil of Baphomet is the official [[Religious symbol|symbol]] of LaVeyan Satanism and the Church of Satan.]]\n'''LaVeyan Satanism''' is a [[religion]] founded in 1966 by the American [[occultism|occultist]] and author [[Anton LaVey|Anton Szandor LaVey]]. Scholars of religion have classified it as a [[new religious movement]] and a form of [[Western esotericism]]. It is one of several different movements that describe themselves as forms of [[Satanism]].\n\nLaVey established LaVeyan Satanism in the U.S. state of [[California]] through the founding of his [[Church of Satan]] on [[Walpurgisnacht]] of 1966, which he proclaimed to be \"the Year One\", ''Anno Satanas''\u2014the first year of the \"Age of Satan\". His ideas were heavily influenced by the ideas and writings of [[Friedrich Nietzsche]] and [[Ayn Rand]]. The church grew under LaVey's leadership, with regional ''[[Grotto (Satanism)|grottos]]'' being founded across the United States. A number of these seceded from the church to form independent Satanic organizations during the early 1970s. In 1975, LaVey abolished the grotto system, after which Satanism became a far less organized movement, although it remained greatly influenced by LaVey's writings. In coming years, members of the church left it to establish their own organisations, also following LaVeyan Satanism, among them John Dewey Allee's First Church of Satan and [[Karla LaVey]]'s [[First Satanic Church]].\n\nThe religion's doctrines are codified in LaVey's book, ''[[The Satanic Bible]]''. The religion is [[materialist]], rejecting the existence of supernatural beings, [[Dualism (philosophy of mind)|body-soul dualism]], and [[Afterlife|life after death]]. Practitioners do not believe that [[Satan]] literally exists and do not worship him. Instead, Satan is viewed as a positive archetype representing [[pride]], [[wiktionary:carnal|carnality]], and [[Age of Enlightenment|enlightenment]]. He is also embraced as a [[symbol]] of defiance against [[Abrahamic religions]] which LaVeyans criticize for suppressing humanity's natural instincts and encouraging irrationality. The religion propagates a [[Naturalism (philosophy)|naturalistic]] worldview, seeing mankind as animals existing in an [[amorality|amoral]] universe. It promotes a philosophy based on [[individualism]] and [[rational egoism|egoism]], coupled with [[Social Darwinism]] and [[anti-egalitarianism]].\n\nLaVeyan Satanism involves the practice of [[Magic (paranormal)|magic]], which encompasses two distinct forms; [[greater and lesser magic]]. Greater magic is a form of [[ritual]] practice and is meant as [[psychodramatic]] [[catharsis]] to focus one's emotional energy for a specific purpose. These rites are based on three major psycho-emotive themes: ''compassion'' ([[love]]), ''destruction'' ([[hate]]), and ''sex'' ([[lust]]).  Lesser magic is the practice of [[Psychological manipulation|manipulation]] by means of [[applied psychology]] and [[Glamour (presentation)|glamour]] (or [[Deception|\"wile and guile\"]]) to bend an individual or situation to one's will.\n\n==Definition==\n{{LaVeyan Satanism sidebar}}\nLaVeyan Satanism &ndash; which is also sometimes termed \"Modern Satanism\"{{sfnm|1a1=Lap|1y=2013|1p=83|2a1=Dyrendal|2y=2013|2p=124}} and \"Rational Satanism\"{{sfnm|1a1=Petersen|1y=2009|1p=224|2a1=Dyrendal|2y=2013|2p=123}} &ndash; is classified by scholars of [[religious studies]] as a [[new religious movement]].{{sfn|Faxneld|Petersen|2013||p=81}} When used, \"Rational Satanism\" is often employed to distinguish the approach of the LaVeyan Satanists from the \"Esoteric Satanism\" embraced by groups like the [[Temple of Set]].{{sfnm|1a1=Dyrendal|1y=2012|1p=370|2a1=Petersen|2y=2012|2p=95}} A number of religious studies scholars have also described it as a form of \"self-religion\" or \"self-spirituality\",{{sfnm|1a1=Harvey|1y=1995|1p=290|2a1=Partridge|2y=2004|2p=82|3a1=Petersen|3y=2009|3pp=224&ndash;225|4a1=Schipper|4y=2010|4p=108|5a1=Faxneld|5a2=Petersen|5y=2013|5p=79}} with religious studies scholar Amina Olander Lap arguing that it should be seen as being both part of the \"prosperity wing\" of the self-spirituality [[New Age]] movement and a form of the [[Human Potential Movement]].{{sfn|Lap|2013|p=84}} Conversely, the scholar of Satanism Jesper Aa. Petersen preferred to treat modern Satanism as a \"cousin\" of the New Age and Human Potential movements.{{sfn|Petersen|2005|p=424}}\n\n{{Quote box\n| title = \n| quote = \"In LaVey's way of thinking, Satanism is both a distinctly new religion, which he himself, without any false modesty, invented and the continuance of an ancient tradition of opposition to the status quo... For LaVey, Satanism is also the religion of the playful provocateur; anything that will shock people out of their unthinking adherence to the status quo is worth thinking about or even doing.\"\n| source = Religious studies scholar Eugene Gallagher.{{sfn|Gallagher|2006|p=165}}\n| align = left\n| width = 30em\n| border = 1px\n| fontsize = 85%\n| title_bg = \n| title_fnt = \n| salign = right\n}}\n\nThe anthropologist Jean La Fontaine described LaVeyan Satanism as having \"both elitist and anarchist elements\", also citing one occult bookshop owner who referred to the church's approach as \"anarchistic hedonism\".{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=96}} In their study of Satanism, the [[religious studies]] scholars Asbj\u00f8rn Dyrendal, [[James R. Lewis (scholar)|James R. Lewis]], and Jesper Aa. Petersen suggested that LaVey viewed his religion as \"an antinomian self-religion for productive misfits, with a cynically [[carnivalesque]] take on life, and no supernaturalism\".{{sfn|Dyrendal|Lewis|Petersen|2016|p=70}} The sociologist of religion [[James R. Lewis (scholar)|James R. Lewis]] even described LaVeyan Satanism as \"a blend of Epicureanism and Ayn Rand's philosophy, flavored with a pinch of ritual magic.\"{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=2}} The historian of religion [[Mattias Gardell]] described LaVey's as \"a rational ideology of egoistic hedonism and self-preservation\",{{sfn|Gardell|2003|p=288}} while [[Nevill Drury]] characterised LaVeyan Satanism as \"a religion of self-indulgence\".{{sfn|Drury|2003|p=188}} It has also been described as an \"institutionalism of [[Niccol\u00f2 Machiavelli|Machiavellian]] self-interest\".{{sfn|Taub|Nelson|1993|p=528}}\n\nThe Church of Satan rejects the legitimacy of any other organizations who claim to be Satanists, dubbing them \"Devil worshipers\".<ref name=Stop>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/national/wp/2014/11/07/the-church-of-satan-wants-you-to-stop-calling-these-devil-worshipping-alleged-murderers-satanists/|title=The Church of Satan wants you to stop calling these 'devil worshiping' alleged murderers Satanists |date=7 November 2014 |website=The Washington Post |last=Ohlheiser |first=Abby |accessdate=2015-11-19}}</ref> Prominent Church leader [[Blanche Barton]] described Satanism as \"an alignment, a lifestyle\".{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=99}} LaVey and the church espoused the view that \"Satanists are born, not made\";{{sfn|Contemporary Religious Satanism: A Critical Anthology|Petersen|2009|p=9}} that they are outsiders by their nature, living as they see fit,{{sfn|The Devil's Party: Satanism in Modernity|Faxneld, Petersen|2013|p=129}} who are self-realized in a religion which appeals to the would-be Satanist's nature, leading them to realize they are Satanists through finding a belief system that is in line with their own perspective and lifestyle.{{sfn|Satanism Today|Lewis|2001|p=330}}\n\n==Belief==\n\n===''The Satanic Bible''===\n{{main|The Satanic Bible}}\n\n''The Satanic Bible'' has been in print since 1969 and has been translated into various languages.{{sfn|Lap|2013|p=85}} Lewis argued that although LaVeyan Satanists do not treat ''The Satanic Bible'' as a sacred text in the way many other religious groups treat their holy texts, it nevertheless is \"treated as an authoritative document which effectively ''functions'' as scripture within the Satanic community\".{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=2}} In particular, Lewis highlighted that many Satanists &ndash; both members of the Church of Satan and other groups &ndash; quote from it either to legitimize their own position or to de-legitimize the positions of others in a debate.{{sfn|Lewis|2002|pp=2, 13}} Many other Satanist groups and individual Satanists who are not part of the Church of Satan also recognize LaVey's work as influential.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=317}}\n\nMany Satanists attribute their conversions or discoveries of Satanism to ''The Satanic Bible'', with 20 percent of respondents to a survey by James Lewis mentioning ''The Satanic Bible'' directly as influencing their conversion.{{sfn|Lewis|2003|p=117}} For members of the church, the book is said to serve not only as a compendium of ideas but also to judge the authenticity of someone's claim to be a Satanist.{{sfn|The Devil's Party: Satanism in Modernity|Faxneld, Petersen|2013|page=115}} LaVey's writings have been described as \"cornerstones\" within the church and its teachings,{{sfn|Petersen|2012|p=114}} and have been supplemented with the writings of its later High Priest, Gilmore, namely his book, ''[[The Satanic Scriptures]]''.{{sfn|Petersen|2012|p=114}}\n\n''The Satanic Bible'' has been described as the most important document to influence contemporary Satanism.{{sfn|Lewis|2003|p = 116}} The book contains the core principles of Satanism, and is considered the foundation of its philosophy and dogma.{{sfn|Lewis|2003|p = 105}} On their website, the Church of Satan urge anyone seeking to learn about LaVeyan Satanism to read ''The Satanic Bible'', stating that doing so is \"tantamount to understanding at least the basics of Satanism\".{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=12}} Petersen noted that it is \"in many ways ''the'' central text of the Satanic milieu\",{{sfn|Petersen|2013|p=232}} with Lap similarly testifying to its dominant position within the wider Satanic movement.{{sfn|Lap|2013|p=85}} [[David G. Bromley]] calls it \"[[Iconoclasm|iconoclastic]]\" and \"the best-known and most influential statement of Satanic theology.\"{{sfn|Bromley|2005|pp=8127\u20138128}} [[Eugene V. Gallagher]] says that Satanists use LaVey's writings \"as lenses through which they view themselves, their group, and the cosmos.\" He also states: \"With a clear-eyed appreciation of true human nature, a love of ritual and pageantry, and a flair for mockery, LaVey's ''Satanic Bible'' promulgated a gospel of self-indulgence that, he argued, anyone who dispassionately considered the facts would embrace.\"{{sfn|Gallagher|2005|p=6530}}\n\n===Atheism and Satan===\n\nLaVey was an [[atheism|atheist]], rejecting the existence of all gods.<ref name=DwD>{{cite web |url=https://www.ozy.com/true-story/my-dinner-with-the-devil/71233/|title=My Dinner With The Devil |date=7 September 2016 |website=OZY |last=Robinson |first=Eugene |accessdate=2018-07-13}}</ref> LaVey and his Church do not espouse a belief in [[Satan]] as an entity who literally exists,{{sfn|Harvey|1995|p=290}} and LaVey did not encourage the worship of Satan as a deity.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=97}} Instead, the use of Satan as a central figure is intentionally symbolic.{{sfn|Petersen|2005|p=430}} LaVey sought to cement his belief system within the [[secularism|secularist]] world-view that derived from [[natural science]], thus providing him with an atheistic basis with which to criticize Christianity and other supernaturalist beliefs.{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2002|1p=4|2a1=Petersen|2y=2005|2p=434}} He legitimized his religion by highlighting what he claimed was its rational nature, contrasting this with what he saw as the supernaturalist irrationality of established religions.{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=4}} He defined Satanism as \"a secular philosophy of rationalism and self-preservation (natural law, animal state), giftwrapping these ideas in religious trappings to add to their appeal.\"{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=336}} In this way, LaVeyan Satanism has been described as an \"antireligious religion\" by van Luijk.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=328}} LaVey did not believe in any [[afterlife]].{{sfn|Maxwell-Stuart|2011|p=198}}\n\n{{Quote box\n| title = \n| quote = If man insists on externalizing his true self in the form of \"God,\" then why fear his true self, in fearing \"God,\"\u2014why praise his true self in praising \"God,\"\u2014why remain externalized from \"God\" {{smallcaps|in order to engage in ritual and religious ceremony in his name?}}<br />Man needs ritual and dogma, but no law states that an ''externalized'' god is necessary in order to engage in ritual and ceremony performed in a god's name! Could it be that when he closes the gap between himself and his \"God\" he sees the demon of pride creeping forth\u2014that very embodiment of Lucifer appearing in his midst?\n| source = LaVey, ''The Satanic Bible''.{{sfn|Harvey|1995|p=291}}\n| align = right\n| width = 30em\n| border = 1px\n| fontsize = 85%\n| title_bg = \n| title_fnt = \n| salign = right\n}}\n\nInstead of worshiping the Devil as a real figure, the image of Satan is embraced because of its association with social non-conformity and rebellion against the dominant system.{{sfnm|1a1=Harvey|1y=1995|1p=290|2a1=La Fontaine|2y=1999|2p=97}} LaVey embraced the iconography of Satan and the label of \"Satanist\" because it shocked people into thinking,{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2001a|1p=17|2a1=Gallagher|2y=2006|2p=165}} and when asked about his religion, stated that \"the reason it's called Satanism is because it's fun, it's accurate and it's productive\".{{sfn|Harvey|1995|p=290}}\n\nLaVey also conceptualised Satan as a symbol of the individual's own vitality,{{sfn|Schipper|2010|p=107}} thus representing an autonomous power within,{{sfn|Schipper|2010|p=106}} and a representation of personal liberty and individualism.{{sfn|Cavaglion|Sela-Shayovitz|2005|p=255}} Throughout ''The Satanic Bible'', the LaVeyan Satanist's view of god is described as the Satanist's true \"self\"\u2014a projection of his or her own personality\u2014not an external deity.{{sfn|Wright|1993|p=143}} In works like ''The Satanic Bible'', LaVey often uses the terms \"god\" and \"Satan\" interchangeably, viewing both as personifications of human nature.{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=287|2a1=Muzzatti|2y=2005|2p=874}}\n\nDespite his professed atheism, some passages of LaVey's writings left room for a literal interpretation of Satan, and some members of his Church understood the Devil as an entity that really existed.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=348}} It is possible that LaVey left some ambivalence in his writings so as not to drive away those Church members who were theistic Satanists.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=355}}\nBoth LaVey's writings and the publications of the church continue to refer to Satan as if he were a real being, in doing so seeking to reinforce the Satanist's self-interest.{{sfn|Harvey|1995|p=291}}\n\nLaVey used Christianity as a negative mirror for his new faith,{{sfn|Schipper|2010|p=109}} with LaVeyan Satanism rejecting the basic principles and theology of Christian belief.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=96}} It views Christianity &ndash; alongside other major religions, and philosophies such as [[humanism]] and [[liberal democracy]] &ndash; as a largely negative force on humanity; LaVeyan Satanists perceive Christianity as a lie which promotes idealism, self-denigration, herd behavior, and irrationality.{{sfn|Faxneld|Petersen|2013|p=80}} LaVeyans view their religion as a force for redressing this balance by encouraging materialism, egoism, stratification, carnality, atheism, and social Darwinism.{{sfn|Faxneld|Petersen|2013|p=80}} LaVey's Satanism was particularly critical of what it understands as Christianity's denial of humanity's animal nature, and it instead calls for the celebration of, and indulgence in, these desires.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=96}} In doing so, it places an emphasis on the carnal rather than the spiritual.{{sfn|Lewis|2001b|p=50}}\n\n===Human nature and society===\n\nLaVeyan Satanism has been characterised as belonging to the [[Right-wing politics|political right]] rather than to the [[Left-wing politics|political left]].{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=326}} The historian of Satanism Ruben van Luijk characterised it as a form of \"anarchism of the Right\".{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=374}} LaVey was anti-egalitarian and elitist, believing in the fundamental inequality of different human beings.{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=289|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=366}} His philosophy was [[Social Darwinist]] in basis,{{sfnm|1a1=La Fontaine|1y=1999|1p=97|2a1=Lap|2y=2013|2p=95|3a1=van Luijk|3y=2016|3p=367}} having been influenced by the writings of [[Herbert Spencer]], [[Friedrich Nietzsche]], and [[Ayn Rand]].{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=287|2a1=Petersen|2y=2005|2p=447|3a1=Lap|3y=2013|3p=95}} LaVey stated that his Satanism was \"just Ayn Rand's philosophy with ceremony and ritual added\".{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2001a|1p=18|2a1=Lewis|2y=2002|2p=9}} Characterising LaVey as a Nietzschean, the religious studies scholar Asbj\u00f8rn Dyrendal nevertheless thought that LaVey's \"personal synthesis seems decidedly his own creation, even though the different ingredients going into it are at times very visible.\"{{sfn|Dyrendal|2012|p=370}} Social Darwinism is particularly noticeable in ''The Book of Satan'', where LaVey uses portions of Redbeard's ''[[Might Is Right]]'', though it also appears throughout in references to man's inherent strength and instinct for self-preservation.{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=4}}\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = left\n\n | image1 = Nietzsche187a.jpg\n | alt1 = Friedrich Nietzsche\n | link1 = [Friedrich Nietzsche]\n\n | image2 = \n | alt2 = Ayn Rand\n | link2 = [Ayn Rand]\n \n| footer = LaVeyan Satanism's views on human nature are influenced by the work of [[Friedrich Nietzsche]] (''pictured'') and [[Ayn Rand]].\n}}\n\nFor LaVey, the human being was explicitly viewed as an animal,{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2002|1p=4|2a1=Gardell|2y=2003|2p=288|3a1=Baddeley|3y=2010|3p=74|4a1=Lap|4y=2013|4p=94}} who thus has no purpose other than [[survival of the fittest]], and who therefore exists in an [[amorality|amoral]] context.{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=4}} He believed that in adopting a philosophical belief in its own superiority above that of the other animals, humankind has become \"the most vicious animal of all\".{{sfn|Lap|2013|p=94}} For LaVey, non-human animals and children represent an ideal, \"the purest form of carnal existence\", because they have not been indoctrinated with Christian or other religious concepts of guilt and shame.{{sfn|Lap|2013|p=95}} His ethical views focused around placing oneself and one's family before others, minding one's own business, and &ndash; for men &ndash; behaving like a [[gentleman]].{{sfn|Gardell|2003|p=289}} In responding to threats and harm, he promoted a policy of ''[[Eye for an eye|lex talionis]]'', for instance reversing a Biblical Christian teaching by stating that \"if a man smite thee on the one cheek, ''smash'' him on the other.\"{{sfn|Gardell|2003|p=289}}\n\nLaVeyan Satanism places great emphasis on the role of [[liberty]] and personal freedom.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=322}} LaVey believed that the ideal Satanist should be individualistic and non-conformist, rejecting what he called the \"colorless existence\" that mainstream society sought to impose on those living within it.{{sfn|Dyrendal|2013|p=129}} He rejected [[consumerism]] and what he called the \"death cult\" of [[fashion]].{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=374}} He praised the human [[Ego (Freudian)|ego]] for encouraging an individual's pride, self-respect, and self-realization and accordingly believed in satisfying the ego's desires.{{sfn|Lap|2013|p=92}} He expressed the view that self-indulgence was a desirable trait,{{sfn|Maxwell-Stuart|2011|p=198}} and that hate and aggression were not wrong or undesirable emotions but that they were necessary and advantageous for survival.{{sfn|Lap|2013|p=94}} Accordingly, he praised the [[Seven Deadly Sins]] as virtues which were beneficial for the individual.{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=288|2a1=Schipper|2y=2010|2p=107}}\n\nSimilarly, LaVey criticized the negative and restrictive attitude to sexuality present in many religions, instead supporting any sexual acts that take place between consenting adults.{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=288|2a1=Lap|2y=2013|2p=91|3a1=Faxneld|3a2=Petersen|3y=2014|3p=168|4a1=van Luijk|4y=2016|4p=321}} His Church welcomed homosexual members from its earliest years,{{sfn|Faxneld|Petersen|2014|p=168}} and he also endorsed celibacy for those who were [[asexuality|asexual]].{{sfn|Faxneld|Petersen|2014|p=168}} He sought to discourage negative feelings of guilt arising from sexual acts such as masturbation and fetishes,{{sfn|Lap|2013|p=91}} and believed that rejecting these sexual inhibitions and guilt would result in a happier and healthier society.{{sfn|Faxneld|Petersen|2014|p=169}} Discussing women, LaVey argued that they should use sex as a tool to manipulate men, in order to advance their own personal power.{{sfn|Faxneld|Petersen|2014|p=170}} Conversely, non-consensual sexual relations, such as [[rape]] and [[child sexual abuse|child molestation]], were denounced by LaVey and his Church.{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=288|2a1=Maxwell-Stuart|2y=2011|2p=198}}\n\nLaVey believed in the imminent demise of Christianity.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=357}} In addition, he believed that society would enter an Age of Satan, in which a generation living in accordance with LaVeyan principles would come to power.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=379}}\nLaVey supported [[eugenics]] and expected it to become a necessity in the future, when it would be used to breed an elite who reflected LaVey's \"Satanic\" principles.{{sfnm|1a1=Lap|1y=2013|1p=95|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=376}} In his view, this elite would be \"superior people\" who displayed the \"Satanic\" qualities of creativity and nonconformity.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=376}} He regarded these traits as capable of hereditary transmission, and made the claim that \"Satanists are born, not made\".{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=376}} He believed that the elite should be siphoned off from the rest of the human \"herd\", with the latter being forced into ghettoes, ideally \"space ghettoes\" located on other planets.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=375}}\nThe anthropologist Jean La Fontaine highlighted an article that appeared in a LaVeyan magazine, ''The Black Flame'', in which one writer described \"a true Satanic society\" as one in which the population consists of \"free-spirited, well-armed, fully-conscious, self-disciplined individuals, who will neither need nor tolerate any external entity 'protecting' them or telling them what they can and cannot do.\"{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=97}} This rebellious approach conflicts with LaVey's firm beliefs in observing the [[rule of law]].{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=97}} Although personally neither a [[fascism|fascist]] nor [[Neo-Nazism|neo-Nazi]],{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=373}} LaVey was on good terms with various neo-Nazi and other right-wing groups operating in the United States.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=368}}\n\n===Magic===\n{{main|Greater and lesser magic}}\n\n[[File:Aleister Crowley.jpg|thumb|right|150px|LaVey's understanding of magic was influenced by the British occultist Aleister Crowley]]\n\nAlthough LaVey's ideas were largely shaped around a secular and scientific world-view, he also expressed a belief in [[magic (paranormal)|magic]].{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2002|1pp=3\u20134|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=336}} Rather than characterising magic as a [[supernatural]] phenomenon, LaVey expressed the view that it was a part of the natural world thus far undiscovered by scientists.{{sfn|Lewis|2002|pp=3\u20134}} Outlined in ''The Satanic Bible'', LaVey defined magic as \"the change in situations or events in accordance with one's will, which would, using normally accepted methods, be unchangeable\",{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1pp=288&ndash;289|2a1=Petersen|2y=2012|2p=95|3a1=Lap|3y=2013|3p=96|4a1=van Luijk|4y=2016|4p=342}} a definition that reflects the influence of the British occultist [[Aleister Crowley]].{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=342}} Although he never explained exactly how he believed that this magical process worked,{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=339}} LaVey stated that magicians could successfully utilise this magical force through intensely imagining their desired goal and thus directing the force of their own willpower toward it.{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2002|1p=4|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=339}} He emphasised the idea that magical forces could be manipulated through \"purely emotional\" rather than intellectual acts.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=339}}\n\nThis practice puts LaVeyan Satanism within a wider tradition of 'high magic' or ceremonial magic,{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=339}} and has also been compared with [[Christian Science]] and [[Scientology]].{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=4}} LaVey adopted beliefs and ideas from older magicians but consciously de-Christianised and Satanised them for his own purposes.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=337}}\nIn presenting himself as applying a scientific perspective on magic, LaVey was likely influenced by Crowley, who had also presented his approach to magic in the same way.{{sfn|Dyrendal|2012|p=376}} However, in contrast to many older ceremonial magicians, LaVey denied that there was any division between [[black magic]] and [[white magic]],{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=289|2a1=Dyrendal|2y=2012|2p=377|3a1=Dyrendal|3a2=Petersen|3a3=Lewis|3y=2016|3p=86}} attributing this dichotomy purely to the \"smug hypocrisy and self-deceit\" of those who called themselves \"white magicians\".{{sfn|Dyrendal|2012|p=377}} He similarly differed from many older magicians who emphasised magic as a practice designed to bring about personal transformation and transcendence; rather, for LaVey magic was employer for material gain, personal influence, to harm enemies, and to gain success in love and sex.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|pp=336\u2013337}}\n\nLaVey defined his system of magic as [[greater and lesser magic]].{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=289|2a1=Petersen|2y=2012|2pp=95\u201396|3a1=Lap|3y=2013|3p=97|4a1=Dyrendal|4a2=Lewis|4a3=Petersen|4y=2016|4p=86}} Greater magic is a form of ritual practice and is meant as psychodramatic catharsis to focus one's emotional energy for a specific purpose. These rites are based on three major psycho-emotive themes: ''compassion'' ([[love]]), ''destruction'' (hate), and ''sex'' (lust).{{sfn|Dyrendal|Lewis|Petersen|2016|p=86}} The space in which a ritual is performed is known as an \"intellectual decompression chamber\",{{sfn|The Invention of Satanism Dyrendal, Petersen|2016|page=89}} where skepticism and disbelief are willfully suspended, thus allowing the magicians to fully express their mental and emotional needs, holding back nothing regarding their deepest feelings and desires. This magic could then be employed to ensure sexual gratification, material gain, personal success, or to curse one's enemies.{{sfn|Gardell|2003|p=289}} LaVey also wrote of \"the balance factor\", insisting that any magical aims should be realistic.{{sfn|Lap|2013|p=98}} These rituals are often considered to be magical acts,{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=98}} with LaVey's Satanism encouraging the practice of [[Magic (paranormal)|magic]] to aid one's selfish ends.{{sfn|Medway|2001|p=21}} Much of Satanic ritual is designed for an individual to carry out alone; this is because concentration is seen as key to performing magical acts.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|pp=98\u201399}}\n\nLesser magic, also referred to an \"everyday\" or \"situational\" magic, is the practice of manipulation by means of applied psychology. LaVey defined it as \"wile and guile obtained through various devices and contrived situations, which when utilized, can create change in accordance with one's will.\"{{sfn|Witchcraft and Magic in Europe, Volume 6: The Twentieth Century|Blecourt, Hutton, Fontaine|1999|p=91}} LaVey wrote that a key concept in lesser magic is the \u201ccommand to look\u201d, which can be accomplished by utilizing elements of \u201csex, sentiment, and wonder\u201d,{{sfn|Controversial New Religions|Lewis, Petersen|p=418}} in addition to the utilization of looks, body language, scents,{{sfn|The Devil's Party: Satanism in Modernity|Faxneld, Petersen|2013|page=97}} color, patterns, and odor.{{sfn|Handbook of Religion and the Authority of Science|Lewis, Hammer|2014|p=90}} This system encourages a form of manipulative role-play, wherein the practitioner may alter several elements of their physical appearance in order to aid them in seducing or \"bewitching\" on object of desire.{{sfn|The Devil's Party: Satanism in Modernity|Faxneld, Petersen|2013|p=97}}\n\nLaVey developed \u201cThe Synthesizer Clock\u201d, the purpose of which is to divide humans into distinct groups of people based primarily on body shape and personality traits.{{sfn|The Devil's Party: Satanism in Modernity|Faxneld, Petersen|2013|p=97}} The synthesizer is modeled as a clock, and based on concepts of [[somatotypes]].{{sfn|Handbook of Religion and the Authority of Science|Petersen|2010|p=67}} The clock is intended to aid a witch in identifying themselves, subsequently aiding in utilizing the \u201cattraction of opposites\u201d to \u201cspellbind\u201d the witch's object of desire by assuming the opposite role.{{sfn|The Devil's Party: Satanism in Modernity|Faxneld, Petersen|2013|p=97}} The successful application of lesser magic is said to be built upon one's understanding of their place on the clock.{{sfn|Sexuality and New Religious Movements|Lewis, Bogdan|2014|p=}} Upon finding your position on the clock, you are encouraged to adapt it as seen fit, and perfect your type by harmonizing its element for better success.{{sfn|The Devil's Party: Satanism in Modernity|Faxneld, Petersen|2013|p=97}} Dyrendal referred to LaVey's techniques as \u201c[[Erving Goffman]] meets [[William Mortensen]]\u201d.{{sfn|Controversial New Religions|Lewis, Petersen|2014|page=418}} Drawing insights from psychology, biology, and sociology,{{sfn|Handbook of Religion and the Authority of Science|Lewis, Hammer|2010|p=89}} Petersen noted that lesser magic combines occult and \u201crejected sciences of body analysis [and] temperaments.\u201d{{sfn|Handbook of Religion and the Authority of Science|Lewis, Hammer|2010|p=68}}\n\n==Basic tenets==\n\nThe \"central convictions\" of LaVeyan Satanism are formulated into three lists, which are regularly reproduced within the Church of Satan's written material.{{sfn|Petersen|2005|p=431}}\n\n===The Nine Satanic Statements===\n[[File:Alchemy sulfur symbol.svg|thumb|right|150px|The [[alchemical symbol]] for [[Sulfur]], as it appears in ''The Satanic Bible'' above the Nine Satanic Statements.]]\n''The Nine Satanic Statements'' are a set of nine assertions made by LaVey in the introductory chapters of ''The Satanic Bible''. They are considered a touchstone of contemporary organized Satanism that constitute, in effect, brief aphorisms that capture Satanic philosophy.{{sfn|Lewis|2001b|p=192}} The first three statements touch on \"indulgence\", \"vital existence\" and \"undefiled wisdom\" which presents a positive view of the Satanist as a carnal, physical and pragmatic being, where enjoyment of physical existence and an undiluted view of this-worldly truth are promoted as the core values of Satanism, combining elements of Darwinism and Epicureanism. Statement four, five and six deal in matters of ethics, through \"kindness to those who deserve it\", \"vengeance\" and \"responsibility to the responsible\", painting a harsh picture of society and human relations by emphasizing justice rather than love. Statements seven, eight and nine reject the dignity of man, sin and the Christian church. Humans are characterized as \"just another animal\", traditional \"sins\" are promoted as means for gratification, and religion as mere business. The adversarial and [[Antinomy|antinomian]] aspect of Satan takes precedence in support of statements four through nine, with non-conformity being presented as a core ideal.{{sfn|Petersen|2011|pp=159-160}}\n\n# Satan represents [[Pleasure|indulgence]] instead of [[abstinence]].\n# Satan represents [[Self-preservation|vital existence]] instead of [[Delusion|spiritual pipe dreams]].\n# Satan represents [[Perspicacity|undefiled wisdom]] instead of hypocritical [[Self-deception|self-deceit]].\n# Satan represents [[Conditional love|kindness to those who deserve it]], instead of [[Unconditional love|love wasted on ingrates]].\n# Satan represents [[Revenge|vengeance]] instead of [[turning the other cheek]].\n# Satan represents [[Accountability|responsibility to the responsible]] instead of concern for [[Victim playing|psychic vampires]].\n# Satan represents man as just another animal who, because of his \"[[Anthropocentrism|divine spiritual and intellectual development]]\", has become the [[Human\u2013wildlife conflict|most vicious animal of all]].\n# Satan represents all of the [[Seven deadly sins|so-called sins]], as they all lead to physical, mental, or emotional gratification.\n# Satan has been the best friend the [[Christian Church|Church]] has ever had, as he has kept it in business all these years.{{sfnm|1a1=Drury|1y=2003|1pp=191&ndash;192|2a1=Baddeley|2y=2010|2p=71|3a1=Van Luijk|3y=2016|3p=297}}\n\n===The Eleven Satanic Rules of the Earth===\n\n# Do not give opinions or advice unless you are asked.\n# Do not tell your troubles to others unless you are sure they want to hear them.\n# When in another's home, show them respect or else do not go there.\n# If a guest in your home annoys you, treat him cruelly and without mercy.\n# Do not make sexual advances unless you are given the mating signal.\n# Do not take that which does not belong to you unless it is a burden to the other person and they cry out to be relieved.\n# Acknowledge the power of magic if you have employed it successfully to obtain your desires. If you deny the power of magic after having called upon it with success, you will lose all you have obtained.\n# Do not complain about anything to which you need not subject yourself.\n# Do not harm little children.\n# Do not kill non-human animals unless you are attacked or for your food.\n# When walking in open territory, bother no one. If someone bothers you, ask him to stop. If he does not stop, destroy him.{{sfn|Drury|2003|pp=192&ndash;193}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.churchofsatan.com/eleven-rules-of-earth/|title=The Eleven Satanic Rules of the Earth|website=Church of Satan|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n===The Nine Satanic Sins===\n\nThese [[sins]], published by LaVey in 1987, outline characteristics Satanists should avoid:<ref>{{cite web\n| title=The Nine Satanic Sins\n| publisher = Learn Religions\n| url=https://www.learnreligions.com/the-nine-satanic-sins-95782\n| accessdate = May 26, 2019\n| author = Catherine Beyer\n}}</ref>\n\n# Stupidity\n# Pretentiousness \n# [[Solipsism]]\n# Self-deceit\n# Herd Conformity\n# Lack of Perspective\n# Forgetfulness of Past Orthodoxies\n# Counterproductive Pride\n# Lack of Aesthetics\n\n==Rites and practices==\n\n===Rituals and ceremonies===\n\nLaVey emphasized that in his tradition, Satanic rites came in two forms, neither of which were acts of worship; in his terminology, \"rituals\" were intended to bring about change, whereas \"ceremonies\" celebrated a particular occasion.{{sfnm|1a1=La Fontaine|1y=1999|1p=98|2a1=Lap|2y=2013|2p=97}} These rituals were often considered to be magical acts,{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=98}} with LaVey's Satanism encouraging the practice of [[Magic (paranormal)|magic]] to aid one's selfish ends.{{sfn|Medway|2001|p=21}} Much of LaVeyan ritual is designed for an individual to carry out alone; this is because concentration is seen as key to performing magical acts.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|pp=98\u201399}} In ''The Satanic Bible'', LaVey described three types of ritual in his religion: sex rituals designed to attract the desired romantic or sexual partner, compassionate rituals with the intent of helping people (including oneself), and destructive magic which seeks to do harm to others.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=98}} In designing these rituals, LaVey drew upon a variety of older sources, with scholar of Satanism Per Faxneld noting that LaVey \"assembled rituals from a hodgepodge of historical sources, literary as well as esoteric\".{{sfn|Faxneld|2013|p=88}}\n\n[[File:Baphomet.png|thumb|left|[[Eliphas Levi]]'s image of [[Baphomet]] is embraced by LaVeyan Satanists as a symbol of duality, fertility, and the \"powers of darkness\", serving as the namesake of their primary insignia, [[The Sigil of Baphomet]].]]\n\nLaVey described a number of rituals in his book, ''[[The Satanic Rituals]]''; these are \"dramatic performances\" with specific instructions surrounding the clothing to be worn, the music to be used, and the actions to be taken.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=97}} This attention to detail in the design of the rituals was intentional, with their pageantry and theatricality intending to engage the participants' senses and aesthetic sensibilities at various levels and enhancing the participants' willpower for magical ends.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|pp=97, 98}} LaVey prescribed that male participants should wear black robes, while older women should wear black, and other women should dress attractively in order to stimulate sexual feelings among many of the men.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=98}} All participants are instructed to wear amulets of either the upturned pentagram or the image of [[Baphomet]].{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=98}}\n\nAccording to LaVey's instructions, on the altar is to be placed an image of Baphomet. This should be accompanied by various candles, all but one of which are to be black. The lone exception is to be a white candle, used in destructive magic, which is kept to the right of the altar.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=98}} Also to be included are a bell which is rung nine times at the start and end of the ceremony, a chalice made of anything but gold, and which contains an alcoholic drink symbolizing the \"Elixir of Life\", a sword that represents aggression, a model phallus used as an [[aspergillum]], a gong, and parchment on which requests to Satan are to be written before being burned.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=98}} Although alcohol was consumed in the church's rites, [[drunkenness]] was frowned upon and the taking of illicit drugs was forbidden.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=100}}\n\nLaVeyan rituals sometimes include anti-Christian blasphemies, which are intended to have a liberating effect on the participants.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=98}}\nIn some of the rituals, a naked woman serves as the altar; in these cases it is made explicit that the woman's body itself becomes the altar, rather than have her simply lying on an existing altar.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=97}} In contrast to longstanding stereotypes about Satanists, there is no place for sexual orgies in LaVeyan ritual.{{sfnm|1a1=La Fontaine|1y=1999|1p=97|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=337}} Neither animal nor human sacrifice takes place.{{sfnm|1a1=La Fontaine|1y=1999|1p=97|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=338}} Children are banned from attending these rituals, with the only exception being the Satanic Baptism, which is specifically designed to involve infants.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=97}}\n\nLaVey also developed his own [[Black Mass]], which was designed as a form of deconditioning to free the participant from any inhibitions that they developed living in Christian society.{{sfnm|1a1=Petersen|1y=2012|1pp=96&ndash;97|2a1=Faxneld|2y=2013|2p=76|3a1=Lap|3y=2013|3p=98}} He noted that in composing the Black Mass rite, he had drawn upon the work of the French fiction writers [[Charles Baudelaire]] and [[Joris-Karl Huysmans]].{{sfn|Faxneld|2013|p=86}} LaVey openly toyed with the use of literature and popular culture in other rituals and ceremonies, thus appealing to artifice, pageantry, and showmanship.{{sfn|Petersen|2012|pp=106&ndash;107}} For instance, he published an outline of a ritual which he termed the \"Call to Cthulhu\" which drew upon the stories of the alien god [[Cthulhu]] authored by American horror writer [[H. P. Lovecraft]]. In this rite, set to take place at night in a secluded location near to a turbulent body of water, a celebrant takes on the role of Cthulhu and appears before the assembled Satanists, signing a pact between them in the language of Lovecraft's fictional \"Old Ones\".{{sfn|Petersen|2012|p=106}}\n\n===Holidays===\n{{main|Satanic holidays}}\n\nLaVey and the Church of Satan deemed an individual's birthday to be the most important day of the year.{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2001b|1p=50|2a1=Gardell|2y=2003|2p=288|3a1=Lap|3y=2013|3p=99|4a1=van Luijk|4y=2016|4p=330}} [[Walpurgisnacht]] (April 30) is celebrated as the date on which LaVey founded his Church.{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2001b|1pp=50&ndash;51|2a1=Gardell|2y=2003|2p=288}} A third annual festival is [[Halloween]], which also has associations with magic and dark entities.{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2001b|1p=51|2a1=Gardell|2y=2003|2p=288}}\n\n===Symbolism===\n[[Image:SamaelLilithGoatPentagram.png|thumb|right|The Sigil of Baphomet]]\nAs a symbol of his Satanic church, LaVey adopted the upturned five-pointed pentagram.{{sfn|Medway|2001|p=26}} The upturned pentagram had previously been used by the French occultist [[Eliphas L\u00e9vi]], and had been adopted by his disciple, [[Stanislas de Guaita]], who merged it with a goat's head in his 1897 book, ''Key of Black Magic''.{{sfn|Medway|2001|p=26}} In the literature and imagery predating LaVey, imagery used to represent the \"satanic\" is denoted by inverted crosses and blasphemous parodies of Christian art. The familiar goat's head inside an inverted pentagram did not become the foremost symbol of Satanism until the founding of the Church of Satan in 1966.{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=20}} LaVey learned of this variant of the symbol after it had been reproduced on the front cover of Maurice Bessy's [[coffee table book]], ''Pictorial History of Magic and the Supernatural''.{{sfnm|1a1=Medway|1y=2001|1p=26|2a1=Lewis|2y=2001b|2p=20}} Feeling that this symbol embodied his philosophy, LaVey decided to adopt it for his Church.{{sfn|Lewis|2001b|p=20}} In its formative years, the church utilized this image on its membership cards, stationary, medallions and most notably above the altar in the ritual chamber of the Black House.{{sfn|Lewis|2001b|p=21}}\n\nDuring the writing of ''The Satanic Bible'', it was decided that a unique version of the symbol should be rendered to be identified exclusively with the church. LaVey created a new version of Guaita's image, one which was geometrically precise, with two perfect circles surrounding the pentagram, the goat head redrawn, and the Hebrew lettering altered to look more serpentine.{{sfn|Lewis|2001b|p=21}} LaVey had this design copyrighted to the church,{{sfn|Lewis|2001b|p=21}} claiming authorship under the pseudonym of \"Hugo Zorilla\".{{sfn|Partridge|2005|p=376}} In doing so, the symbol &ndash; which came to be known as the [[Sigil of Baphomet]]{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2001b|1p=20|2a1=Partridge|2y=2005|2p=376}} &ndash; came to be closely associated with Satanism in the public imagination.{{sfn|Lewis|2001b|p=20}}\n\n==History==\n\n===Origins: 1966\u201372===\nAlthough there were forms of religious Satanism that predated the creation of LaVeyan Satanism\u2014namely those propounded by [[Stanis\u0142aw Przybyszewski]] and [[Ben Kadosh]]\u2014these had no unbroken lineage of succession to LaVey's form.{{sfn|Faxneld|2013|p=75}} For this reason, the sociologist of religion [[Massimo Introvigne]] stated that \"with few exceptions, LaVey is at the origins of all contemporary Satanism\".{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=299}} Similarly, the historian Ruben van Luijk claimed that the creation of LaVeyan Satanism marked \"the actual beginning of Satanism as a religion such as it is practiced in the world today\".{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=297}}\n\nAfter he came to public attention, LaVey shielded much of his early life in secrecy, and little is known about it for certain.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=295}} He had been born in [[Chicago]] as Howard Stanton Levey in either March or April 1930.{{sfnm|1a1=Dyrendal|1a2=Lewis|1a3=Petersen|1y=2016|1p=51|2a1=Introvigne|2y=2016|2p=300}} He was of mixed Ukrainian, Russian, and German ancestry.{{sfn|Dyrendal|Lewis|Petersen|2016|p=51}} He claimed to have worked in the [[circus]] and [[carnival]] in the years following the [[Second World War]],{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=301}} and in later years, he also alleged that he worked at the San Francisco Orchestra, although this never existed.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=301}} He also claimed to have had a relationship with a young [[Marilyn Monroe]], although this too was untrue.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|pp=300\u2013301}}\n\nBy the 1960s he was living at 6114 California Street in San Francisco, a house that he had inherited from his parents.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|pp=294, 296}} He took an interest in occultism and amassed a large collection of books on the subject.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=296}} At some point between 1957 and 1960 he began hosting classes at his house every Friday in which lectures on occultism and other subjects were given.{{sfn|Dyrendal|Lewis|Petersen|2016|p=52}} Among the topics covered were [[freak]]s, [[extra-sensory perception]], [[Spiritualism]], [[cannibalism]], and historical methods of [[torture]].{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=296}} An informal group established around these lectures, which came to be known as the Magic Circle.{{sfnm|1a1=Dyrendal|1a2=Lewis|1a3=Petersen|1y=2016|1p=52|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=296}} Among those affiliated with this gathering were the filmmaker and [[Thelema|Thelemite]] occultist [[Kenneth Anger]],{{sfn|Dyrendal|Lewis|Petersen|2016|p=53}} and the anthropologist [[Michael Harner]], who later established the [[core shamanism]] movement.{{sfn|Dyrendal|Lewis|Petersen|2016|p=53}}\n\nLaVey likely began preparations for the formation of his [[Church of Satan]] in either 1965 or early 1966,{{sfn|Dyrendal|Lewis|Petersen|2016|p=52}} and it was officially founded on [[Walpurgisnacht]] 1966.{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2002|1p=5|2a1=Gardell|2y=2003|2p=285|3a1=Baddeley|3y=2010|3p=71|4a1=Dyrendal|4a2=Lewis|4a3=Petersen|4y=2016|4p=52}} He then declared that 1966 marked Year One of the new Satanic era.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=297}} It was the first organized church in modern times to be devoted to the figure of Satan,{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=5}} and according to Faxneld and Petersen, the church represented \"the first public, highly visible, and long-lasting organisation which propounded a coherent satanic discourse\".{{sfn|Faxneld|Petersen|2013|p=81}} Its early members were the attendees of LaVey's Magic Circle, although it soon began attracting new recruits.{{sfn|Dyrendal|Lewis|Petersen|2016|p=53}} Many of these individuals were sadomasochists or homosexuals, attracted by the LaVeyan openness to different sexual practices.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=346}} LaVey had painted his house black,{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=296}} with it becoming known as \"the [[Black House (Church of Satan)|Black House]]\",{{sfnm|1a1=Petersen|1y=2005|1p=428|2a1=Baddeley|2y=2010|2pp=66, 71|3a1=Dyrendal|3a2=Lewis|3a3=Petersen|3y=2016|3p=53}} and it was here that weekly rituals were held every Friday night.{{sfn|Dyrendal|Lewis|Petersen|2016|p=53}}\n\nLaVey played up to his Satanic associations by growing a pointed beard and wearing a black cloak and inverted pentagram.{{sfn|Drury|2003|p=188}} He added to his eccentric persona by obtaining unusual pets, including a lion that was kept caged in his back garden.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=296}} Describing himself as the \"High Priest of Satan\",{{sfn|Drury|2003|p=197}} LaVey defined his position within the church as \"monarchical in nature, papal in degree and absolute in power\".{{sfn|Gardell|2003|p=287}} He led the churches' governing Council of Nine,{{sfn|Gardell|2003|p=287}} and implemented a system of five initiatory levels that the LaVeyan Satanist could advance through by demonstrating their knowledge of LaVeyan philosophy and their personal accomplishments in life.{{sfn|Gardell|2003|p=287}} These were known as Apprentice Satanist I\u00b0, Witch or Warlock II\u00b0, Priest or Priestess of Mendes III\u00b0, Magister IV\u00b0, and Magus V\u00b0.{{sfn|Drury|2003|p=197}}\n\n{{Quote box\n| title = \n| quote = Never one for theory, LaVey created a belief system somewhere between religion, philosophy, psychology, and carnival (or circus), freely appropriating science, mythology, fringe beliefs, and play in a potent mix. The core goal was always indulgence and vital existence, based on the devices and desires of the [[self-made man]].\n| source = \u2014 Per Faxneld and Jesper Petersen.{{sfn|Faxneld|Petersen|2013|p=79}}\n| align = left\n| width = 30em\n| border = 1px\n| fontsize = 85%\n| title_bg = \n| title_fnt = \n| salign = right\n}}\n\nThe church experienced its \"golden age\" from 1966 to 1972, when it had a strong media presence.{{sfn|Petersen|2013|p=136}}  In February 1967, LaVey held a much publicized Satanic wedding, which was followed by the Satanic baptism of his daughter Zeena in May, and then a Satanic funeral in December.{{sfnm|1a1=Petersen|1y=2005|1p=438|2a1=Baddeley|2y=2010|2p=71|3a1=Introvigne|3y=2016|3p=309|4a1=van Luijk|4y=2016|4p=297}} Another publicity-attracting event was the \"Topless Witch Revue\", a nightclub show held on San Francisco's North Beach; the use of topless women to attract attention alienated a number of the church's early members.{{sfnm|1a1=Dyrendal|1a2=Lewis|1a3=Petersen|1y=2016|1p=54|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=346}} Through these and other activities, he soon attracted international media attention, being dubbed \"the Black Pope\".{{sfn|Baddeley|2010|p=71}} He also attracted a number of celebrities to join his Church, most notably [[Sammy Davis Junior]] and [[Jayne Mansfield]].{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=286|2a1=Baddeley|2y=2010|2p=72|3a1=Schipper|3y=2010|3pp=105&ndash;106}} LaVey also established branches of the church, known as ''grottos'', in various parts of the United States.{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=287|2a1=Baddeley|2y=2010|2p=74}} He may have chosen the term ''grotto'' over ''[[coven]]'' because the latter term had come to be used by practitioners of the modern Pagan religion of [[Wicca]].{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=344}} These included the Babylon Grotto in [[Detroit]], the Stygian Grotto in [[Dayton]], and the Lilith Grotto in [[New York City]].{{sfn|Baddeley|2010|p=74}} In 1971, a Dutch follower of LaVey's, Maarten Lamers, established his own Kerk van Satan grotto in [[Amsterdam]].{{sfnm|1a1=Introvigne|1y=2016|1p=519|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2pp=344\u2013345}}\n\nAs a result of the success of the film ''[[Rosemary's Baby (film)|Rosemary's Baby]]'' and the concomitant growth of interest in Satanism, an editor at [[Avon Books]], Peter Mayer, approached LaVey and commissioned him to write a book, which became ''[[The Satanic Bible]]''.{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2002|1p=8|2a1=Baddeley|2y=2010|2p=72}} While part of the text was LaVey's original writing, other sections of the book consisted of direct quotations from [[Arthur Desmond]]'s right-wing tract ''[[Might is Right]]'' and the occultist [[Aleister Crowley]]'s version of [[John Dee]]'s ''Enochian Keys''.{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2002|1p=8|2a1=Introvigne|2y=2016|2p=315}} There is evidence that LaVey was inspired by the writings of the American philosopher [[Ayn Rand]]; and while accusations that he plagiarized her work in ''The Satanic Bible'' have been denied by one author, {{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=9}} Chris Mathews stated that \"LaVey stole selectively and edited lightly\" and that his \"Satanism at times closely parallels Ayn Rand's [[Objectivism (Ayn Rand)|Objectivist philosophy]].\"{{sfn|Mathews|2009|p=65-66}} The book ''The Satanic Bible'' served to present LaVey's ideas to a far wider audience than they had previously had.{{sfn|Baddeley|2010|p=72}} In 1972, he published a sequel, ''The Satanic Rituals''.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=298}}\n\nLaVey's Church emerged at a point in American history when Christianity was on the decline as many of the nation's youth broke away from their parental faith and explored alternative systems of religiosity.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=298}} The milieu in which LaVey's Church was operating was dominated by the [[counterculture of the 1960s]]; his Church reflected some of its concerns &ndash; free love, alternative religions, freedom from church and state &ndash; but ran contrary to some of the counterculture's other main themes, such as peace and love, compassion, and the use of mind-altering drugs.{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=295|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=298}} He expressed condemnation of the [[hippies]]; in one ritual he hung an image of [[Timothy Leary]] upside down while stamping on a tablet of [[LSD]].{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=299}}\n\n===Later development: 1972&ndash;present===\n\n[[File:Karla LaVey.jpg|right|thumb|Karla LaVey, founder of the First Satanic Church, in 2012]]\n\nLaVey ceased conducting group rituals and workshops in his home in 1972.{{sfnm|1a1=Lap|1y=2013|1p=84|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=345}}\nIn 1973, church leaders in Michigan, Ohio, and Florida split to form their own Church of Satanic Brotherhood, however this disbanded in 1974 when one of its founders publicly converted to Christianity.{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=7}} Subsequently, Church members based in Kentucky and Indiana left to found the [[Ordo Templi Satanis]].{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=7}} In 1975, LaVey disbanded all grottos, leaving the organisation as a membership-based group that existed largely on paper.{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2002|1p=7|2a1=Lap|2y=2013|2p=84|3a1=Introvigne|3y=2016|3p=518}} He claimed that this had been necessary because the grottos had come to be dominated by social misfits who had not benefitted the church as a whole.{{sfn|Gardell|2003|p=287}} In a private letter, he expressed frustration that despite growing church membership, \"brain surgeons and Congressmen are still in short supply\".{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|pp=346\u2013347}} He also announced that thenceforth all higher degrees in the church would be awarded in exchange for contributions of cash, real estate, or valuable art.{{sfnm|1a1=Drury|1y=2003|1p=193|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=347}} Dissatisfied with these actions, in 1975, the high-ranking Church member Michael Aquino left to found his own Satanic organisation, the [[Temple of Set]],{{sfnm|1a1=Drury|1y=2003|1pp=193&ndash;194|2a1=Gallagher|2y=2006|2p=160|3a1=Schipper|3y=2010|3p=105}} which differed from LaVey's Church by adopting a belief that Satan literally existed.{{sfn|Schipper|2010|p=109}} According to Lap, from this point on Satanism became a \"splintered and disorganized movement\".{{sfn|Lap|2013|p=84}}\n\nBetween the abolition of the grotto system in 1975 and the establishment of the [[internet]] in the mid-1990s, ''The Satanic Bible'' remained the primary means of propagating Satanism.{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=2}} During this period, a decentralized, anarchistic movement of Satanists developed that was shaped by many of the central themes that had pervaded LaVey's thought and which was expressed in ''The Satanic Bible''.{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=4}} Lewis argued that in this community, ''The Satanic Bible'' served as a \"quasi-scripture\" because these independent Satanists were able to adopt certain ideas from the book while merging them with ideas and practices drawn from elsewhere.{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=4}}\n\nDuring the late 1980s, LaVey returned to the limelight, giving media interviews, attracting further celebrities, and reinstating the grotto system.{{sfn|Gardell|2003|p=287}} In 1984 he separated from his wife, Diane Hegarty, and began a relationship with Blanche Barton,{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|pp=512\u2013513}} who was his personal assistant.{{sfn|Lewis|2001b|p=51}} In 1988 Hegarty brought a court case against LaVey, claiming that he she owned half of the church and LaVey's Black House. The court found in Hegarty's favour, after which LaVey immediately declared bankruptcy.{{sfnm|1a1=Introvigne|1y=2016|1p=516|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2pp=377\u2013378}} In May 1992, the ex-couple reached a settlement. The Black House was sold to a wealthy friend, the property developer Donald Werby, who agreed to allow LaVey to continue living at the residence for free.{{sfnm|1a1=Introvigne|1y=2016|1p=516|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=378}} Also in 1992, LaVey published his first book in twenty years, ''The Devil's Notebook''.{{sfn|Gardell|2003|p=287}} This was followed by the posthumous ''Satan Speaks'' in 1998, which included a foreword from the rock singer [[Marilyn Manson]],{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=287|2a1=Introvigne|2y=2016|2p=516}} who was a priest in the church.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=384}}\n\nIn his final years, LaVey suffered from a heart condition, displayed increasing paranoia, and died in October 1997.{{sfnm|1a1=Introvigne|1y=2016|2p=516|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2pp=378\u2013379}} In November, the church announced that it would subsequently be run by two High Priestesses of joint rank, Barton and LaVey's daughter [[Karla LaVey]].{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=516}} That same year, the church established an official website.{{sfn|Petersen|2013|p=140}} Barton attempted to purchase the Black House from Werby, but was unable to raise sufficient funds; the building had fallen into disrepair and was demolished in 2001, subsequently being replaced with an apartment block.{{sfnm|1a1=Introvigne|1y=2016|1p=516|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=380}} A disagreement subsequently emerged between Barton and Karla, resulting in an agreement that Barton would retain legal ownership of the name and organization of the church while LaVey's personal belongings and copyrights would be distributed among his three children, Karla, Zeena, and Satan Xerxes.{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=287|2a1=Introvigne|2y=2016|2pp=516\u2013517}} Barton stood down as High Priestess in 2002, although continued to chair the church's Council of Nine.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=517}} The headquarters of the church were then moved from San Francisco to New York, where [[Peter H. Gilmore]] was appointed the church's High Priest, and his wife Peggy Nadramia as its High Priestess.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=517}}\n\n[[File:Peter H Gilmore 2 by David Shankbone.jpg|thumb|left|Peter Gilmore, High Priest of the Church of Satan]]\n\nAfter LaVey's death, conflict over the nature of Satanism intensified within the Satanic community.{{sfn|Petersen|2013|p=139}} At Halloween 1999 Karla established the [[First Satanic Church]], which uses its website to promote the idea that it represents a direct continuation of the original Church of Satan as founded by Anton LaVey.{{sfnm|1a1=Gallagher|1y=2006|1p=162|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=380}} Other LaVeyan groups appeared elsewhere in the United States. An early member of the Church of Satan, John Dewey Allee, established his own First Church of Satan, claiming allegiance to LaVey's original teachings and professing that LaVey himself had deviated from them in later life.{{sfn|Gallagher|2006|p=162}} In 1986, Paul Douglas Valentine founded the New York City-based [[World Church of Satanic Liberation]], having recruited many of its members through [[Herman Slater]]'s Magickal Childe esoteric store. Its membership remained small and it was discontinued in 2011.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=517}} In 1991, the Embassy of Lucifer was established by the Canadian [[Tsirk Susuej]], which was influenced by LaVeyan teachings but held that Satan was a real entity.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=518}} Splinter groups from Susuej's organisation included the Embassy of Satan in [[Stewart, British Columbia]], and the Luciferian Light Group in [[Baltimore]].{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=518}}\n\nLaVeyan groups also cropped up elsewhere in the world, with a particular concentration in Scandinavia; most of these Scandinavian groups either split from the Church of Satan or never affiliated with it.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=520}} These included the Svenska Satanistkyrkan and the Det Norske Sataniske Samfunn,{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=520}} as well as the Prometheus Grotten of the Church of Satan which was established in Denmark in 1997 but which officially seceded in 2000.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=520}} A Satanic Church was also established in [[Estonia]] based on the LaVeyan model; it later renamed itself the [[Order of the Black Widow]].{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|pp=519\u2013520}}\n\nThe Church of Satan became increasingly doctrinally-rigid and focused on maintaining the purity of LaVeyan Satanism.{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2002|1p=5|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=380}} The church's increased emphasis on their role as the bearer of LaVey's legacy was partly a response to the growth in non-LaVeyan Satanists.{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=5}} Some Church members &ndash; including Gilmore{{sfn|Petersen|2013|p=140}} &ndash; claimed that only they were the \"real\" Satanists and that those belonging to different Satanic traditions were \"pseudo\" Satanists.{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2002|1p=5|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=380}} After examining many of these claims on the church's website, Lewis concluded that it was \"''obsessed'' with shoring up its own legitimacy by attacking the heretics, especially those who criticize LaVey\".{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=7}} Meanwhile, the church experienced an exodus of its membership in the 2000s, with many of these individuals establishing new groups online.{{sfn|Petersen|2013|p=139}} Although the church's public face had performed little ceremonial activity since the early 1970s, in June 2006 they held a Satanic 'High Mass' in Los Angeles to mark the church's fortieth birthday.{{sfn|Petersen|2012|pp=115&ndash;116}}\n\n==Demographics==\n\nMembership levels of the Church of Satan are hard to determine, as the organisation has not released such information.{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=287|2a1=Petersen|2y=2005|2p=430}} During its early years, the church claimed a membership of around 10,000, although defectors subsequently claimed that the number was only in the hundreds.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=344}} Membership was largely, although not exclusively, white.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|pp=369\u2013370}} LaVey recognised this, suggesting that the church appealed particularly to white Americans because they lacked the strong sense of ethnic identity displayed by African-Americans and Hispanic Americans.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=370}} The historian of religion [[Massimo Introvigne]] suggested that it had never had more than 1000 or 2000 members at its height, but that LaVeyan ideas had had a far greater influence through LaVey's books.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=320}} Membership is gained by paying $225 and filling out a registration statement,{{sfn|Petersen|2005|p=430}} and thus initiates are bestowed with lifetime memberships and not charged annual fees.{{sfn|Gardell|2003|p=287}}\n\nLa Fontaine thought it likely that the easy availability of LaVey's writings would have encouraged the creation of various Satanic groups that were independent of the Church of Satan itself.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=100}} In ''The Black Flame'', a number of groups affiliated with the church have been mentioned, most of which are based in the United States and Canada although two groups were cited as having existed in New Zealand.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=100}} In his 2001 examination of Satanists, the sociologist [[James R. Lewis (scholar)|James R. Lewis]] noted that, to his surprise, his findings \"consistently pointed to the centrality of LaVey's influence on modern Satanism\".{{sfn|Lewis|2001a|p=5}} \"Reflecting the dominant influence of Anton LaVey's thought\", Lewis noted that the majority of those whom he examined were atheists or agnostics, with 60% of respondents viewing Satanism as a symbol rather than a real entity.{{sfn|Lewis|2001a|p=11}} 20% of his respondents described ''The Satanic Bible'' as the most important factor that attracted them to Satanism.{{sfn|Lewis|2001a|p=15}} Elsewhere, Lewis noted that few Satanists who weren't members of the Church of Satan would regard themselves as \"orthodox LaVeyans\".{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=2}}\n \nExamining the number of LaVeyan Satanists in Britain, in 1995 the religious studies scholar Graham Harvey noted that the Church of Satan had no organized presence in the country.{{sfn|Harvey|1995|p=290}} He noted that LaVey's writings were widely accessible in British bookshops,{{sfn|Harvey|1995|p=290}} and La Fontaine suggested that there may have been individual Church members within the country.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=100}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal bar|Religion|Philosophy}}\n*{{annotated link|Contemporary Religious Satanism|''Contemporary Religious Satanism''}}\n*{{annotated link|Satanic ritual abuse}}\n*{{annotated link|Devil in popular culture}}\n*{{annotated link|Conceptions of God}}\n*{{annotated link|Nontheistic religions}}\n*{{annotated link|Religious naturalism}}\n*{{annotated link|Secular religion}}\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{Refbegin|30em|indent=yes}}\n* {{cite contribution |last=Alfred |first=A. |contribution=The Church of Satan |title=The New Religious Consciousness |editor=C. Glock |editor2=R. Bellah|location=Berkeley |pages=180&ndash;202 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title=Lucifer Rising: Sin, Devil Worship & Rock n' Roll |last=Baddeley |first=Gavin |location=London |publisher=Plexus |year=