n=978-0199315314 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Schipper |first=Bernd U. |title=From Milton to Modern Satanism: The History of the Devil and the Dynamics between Religion and Literature |journal=Journal of Religion in Europe |volume=3 |issue=1 |year=2010 |pages=103&ndash;124 |doi=10.1163/187489210X12597396698744  |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Taub|first1=Diane E.|last2=Nelson|first2=Lawrence D.|title=Satanism in Contemporary America: Establishment or Underground?|journal=The Sociological Quarterly|date=August 1993|volume=34|issue=3|pages=523\u2013541|ref=harv|doi=10.1111/j.1533-8525.1993.tb00124.x}}\n* {{cite book |first=Ruben |last=van Luijk |year=2016 |title=Children of Lucifer: The Origins of Modern Religious Satanism |location=Oxford |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780190275105 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Wright|first=Lawrence|title=Saints & Sinners|year=1993|publisher=Alfred A. Knopf, Inc|location=New York|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1bwDrFdnNcsC|isbn=0-394-57924-0|authorlink=Lawrence Wright|ref=harv}}\n\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.churchofsatan.com/ Official Church of Satan website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120725045139/http://www.underworldamusements.net/blog/2011/satanism-as-weltanschauung/ \u201cSatanism as Weltanschauung\u201d, the philosophy of the Church of Satan (presented by Kevin I. Slaughter at the Maryland Institute College of Art)]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=T5fxA6yhwTY/ \"Satan as Rebel Hero: Henry M. Tichenor and the Radical Anti-religious (presented by Kevin I. Slaughter and Robert Merciless at SkeptiCamp DC on October 3, 2010, College Park, MD)]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BzlOtvDFjx0/ \"What Does Satanism Mean to You?\" (Interview with members of the Church of Satan)]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7uiJsAp82jg/ \"Inside the Church of Satan (Documentary)]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kkmuV5R_O6g/ 9sense Podcast interview with Peter H. Gilmore on Walpurgisnacht.]\n*{{wikinews-inline|Satanism: An interview with Church of Satan High Priest Peter Gilmore}}\n\n{{LaVeyan Satanism}}\n{{Greater and Lesser Magic}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Laveyan Satanism}}\n[[Category:Satanism| ]]\n[[Category:Church of Satan]]\n[[Category:New religious movements]]\n[[Category:Philosophical movements]]\n[[Category:Self religions]]\n", "name_user": "71.29.140.4", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(Added content)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LaVeyan_Satanism"}
{"title_page": "Armando Walle", "text_new": "{{short description|Texas politician}}\n{{Infobox Officeholder \n| name = Armando Walle\n| state_house = Texas\n| state = Texas\n| district = 140th\n| predecessor = [[Kevin Bailey (politician)|Kevin Bailey]]\n| term_start = January 13, 2009\n| residence = [[Houston, Texas]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of Houston]]\n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] \n| religion = [[Roman Catholic]]\n}}\n'''Armando Lucio Walle'''<ref>{{cite web |title=Legislative Reference Library {{!}} Legislators and Leaders {{!}} Member profile |url=https://lrl.texas.gov/legeLeaders/members/memberDisplay.cfm?memberID=5671&searchparams=chamber=~city=~countyID=0~RcountyID=~district=140~first=~gender=~last=~leaderNote=~leg=~party=~roleDesc=~Committee= |website=lrl.texas.gov |accessdate=23 December 2019}}</ref> is a representative in the [[Texas House of Representatives]], representing the 140th district in [[Houston, Texas]]. Walle is the Deputy Floor Leader of the Texas House Democrats.  Walle was named Harris County COVID-19 Pandemic Recovery Czar by Harris County Judge Lina Hidaldgo|url=https://www.chron.com/coronavirus/article/Houston-coronavirus-updates-What-you-need-to-15212389.php||accessdate=20 April 2020|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nWalle was born and raised in Houston; he was the oldest of five children. While in high school, Walle worked at a [[taquer\u00eda]] and interned for [[Houston City Council|Houston Councilwoman]] Carol Mimms Galloway.<ref name=\"Taking office\">{{cite news|last=Feldman|first=Claudia|title=Armando Walle steps into role as state representative|url=http://www.chron.com/life/article/Armando-Walle-steps-into-role-as-state-1742364.php|accessdate=5 September 2013|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|date=18 January 2009}}</ref> Walle also played football in middle school and high school, and credits his football coach as a major inspiration for his desire to be a role model.<ref name=Cougar>{{cite news|last=Sifuentes|first=Andrea|title=Q&A with Rep. Armando Walle|url=http://thedailycougar.com/2013/06/24/qa-rep-armando-walle/|accessdate=5 September 2013|newspaper=The Daily Cougar|date=24 June 2013}}</ref> Walle graduated from MacArthur High School and earned a B.S. in political science from the [[University of Houston]]. Armando is married to Debbie Dimas Walle, and has one son, Armando Pedro Walle.<ref name=\"House bio\">{{cite web|title=Rep. Walle, Armando|url=http://www.house.state.tx.us/members/member-page/?district=140#member-biography|publisher=Texas House of Representatives|accessdate=5 September 2013}}</ref> As of 2013, Walle was pursuing a J.D. from the [[University of Houston]].<ref name=\"Cougar\"/>\n\n==Texas House of Representatives==\nWalle worked for US Representatives [[Gene Green]] and [[Sheila Jackson Lee]] prior to being elected to the [[Texas House of Representatives]].<ref name=\"House bio\"/> Walle left his job with Green to take on nine-term incumbent Democrat Kevin Bailey, ultimately upsetting the incumbent in the Democratic primary. With no Republican opponent in the general election, Walle took office in 2009.<ref name=\"Taking office\"/> Walle serves as Deputy Floor Leader of his caucus, and serves on the Business & Industry Committee, serves as Vice Chair of the Land & Resource Management Committee, and serves on the Federalism & Fiscal Responsibility Committee.<ref name=\"House bio\"/>\n\nIn 2013, Walle supported the protests of Houston fast food workers seeking higher wages.<ref name=Protests>{{cite news|last=Hlavaty|first=Craig|title=Fast food wage protests hit Houston|url=http://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/article/Fast-food-wage-protests-hit-Houston-4770440.php|accessdate=5 September 2013|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|date=29 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/102289/armando-walle#.Uif9wzbrxP0 Vote Smart profile]\n\n{{Texas House of Representatives}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walle, Armando}}\n[[Category:Texas Democrats]]\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Texas politician}}\n{{Infobox Officeholder \n| name = Armando Walle\n| state_house = Texas\n| state = Texas\n| district = 140th\n| predecessor = [[Kevin Bailey (politician)|Kevin Bailey]]\n| term_start = January 13, 2009\n| residence = [[Houston, Texas]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of Houston]]\n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] \n| religion = [[Roman Catholic]]\n}}\n'''Armando Lucio Walle'''<ref>{{cite web |title=Legislative Reference Library {{!}} Legislators and Leaders {{!}} Member profile |url=https://lrl.texas.gov/legeLeaders/members/memberDisplay.cfm?memberID=5671&searchparams=chamber=~city=~countyID=0~RcountyID=~district=140~first=~gender=~last=~leaderNote=~leg=~party=~roleDesc=~Committee= |website=lrl.texas.gov |accessdate=23 December 2019}}</ref> is a representative in the [[Texas House of Representatives]], representing the 140th district in [[Houston, Texas]]. Walle is the Deputy Floor Leader of the Texas House Democrats.  Walle was named Harris County COVID-19 Pandemic Recovery Czar by Harris County Judge Lina Hidaldgo|url=https://www.chron.com/coronavirus/article/Houston-coronavirus-updates-What-you-need-to-15212389.php|\n\n==Early life and education==\nWalle was born and raised in Houston; he was the oldest of five children. While in high school, Walle worked at a [[taquer\u00eda]] and interned for [[Houston City Council|Houston Councilwoman]] Carol Mimms Galloway.<ref name=\"Taking office\">{{cite news|last=Feldman|first=Claudia|title=Armando Walle steps into role as state representative|url=http://www.chron.com/life/article/Armando-Walle-steps-into-role-as-state-1742364.php|accessdate=5 September 2013|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|date=18 January 2009}}</ref> Walle also played football in middle school and high school, and credits his football coach as a major inspiration for his desire to be a role model.<ref name=Cougar>{{cite news|last=Sifuentes|first=Andrea|title=Q&A with Rep. Armando Walle|url=http://thedailycougar.com/2013/06/24/qa-rep-armando-walle/|accessdate=5 September 2013|newspaper=The Daily Cougar|date=24 June 2013}}</ref> Walle graduated from MacArthur High School and earned a B.S. in political science from the [[University of Houston]]. Armando is married to Debbie Dimas Walle, and has one son, Armando Pedro Walle.<ref name=\"House bio\">{{cite web|title=Rep. Walle, Armando|url=http://www.house.state.tx.us/members/member-page/?district=140#member-biography|publisher=Texas House of Representatives|accessdate=5 September 2013}}</ref> As of 2013, Walle was pursuing a J.D. from the [[University of Houston]].<ref name=\"Cougar\"/>\n\n==Texas House of Representatives==\nWalle worked for US Representatives [[Gene Green]] and [[Sheila Jackson Lee]] prior to being elected to the [[Texas House of Representatives]].<ref name=\"House bio\"/> Walle left his job with Green to take on nine-term incumbent Democrat Kevin Bailey, ultimately upsetting the incumbent in the Democratic primary. With no Republican opponent in the general election, Walle took office in 2009.<ref name=\"Taking office\"/> Walle serves as Deputy Floor Leader of his caucus, and serves on the Business & Industry Committee, serves as Vice Chair of the Land & Resource Management Committee, and serves on the Federalism & Fiscal Responsibility Committee.<ref name=\"House bio\"/>\n\nIn 2013, Walle supported the protests of Houston fast food workers seeking higher wages.<ref name=Protests>{{cite news|last=Hlavaty|first=Craig|title=Fast food wage protests hit Houston|url=http://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/article/Fast-food-wage-protests-hit-Houston-4770440.php|accessdate=5 September 2013|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|date=29 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/102289/armando-walle#.Uif9wzbrxP0 Vote Smart profile]\n\n{{Texas House of Representatives}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walle, Armando}}\n[[Category:Texas Democrats]]\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Elliehutto", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added source", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Armando_Walle"}
{"title_page": "Alat tribe", "text_new": "'''Alat''' (a.k.a '''Ala-at''', '''Ala''', '''Alachin''', '''Alagchin''', '''Alchin''', '''Alchi''', '''Alayuntlqu''', '''Ulayundlu\u011f''' (''\"[[piebald]] horse\"'', pinto); '''Boma''' \u99c1\u99ac \"piebald horse\", '''Helai''' \u8cc0\u8cf4, '''Helan''' \u8cc0\u862d, '''Hela''', '''Bila''') are one of the salient [[Turkic peoples|Turkic]] tribes known from Chinese annals, Bactrian inscriptions,<ref>Sims-Williams (2005). ''Some Bactrian Seal-Inscriptions // Afghanistan, ancien carrefour entre l\u2019est et l\u2019ouest'', ed. O. Bopearachchi and M.-F.  Boussac, pp. 335\u201346</ref> and [[Arab]] and [[Persian people|Persian]] medieval geographers as a prominent tribe that played a distinguished role in the history of Eurasia.They are also known as Khalaj, and Khalaches.\n\nLiterature on Alats is very rich; Alats were a subject of study by ''[[Old Book of Tang|Tangshu]]'',  ''[[Jiu Tangshu]]'', ''[[Tang Huiyao]]'', N.Ya. Bichurin, S.E. Malov, N.A. Aristov, [[Grigory Grum-Grshimailo]], Yu. Nemeth, G. H\u043eworth, P. Pelliot, L. Hambis, and others.\n\n==Name==\nIn ancient Turkic lexicon, the meaning of \"[[skewbald]]\" (horse) is expressed with the terms \"''ala''\" or \"''alagchin''\" still active now in composite expressions. Tang Huiyao mentioned, right after the [[Ashina tribe]], a tribe named ''Geluozhiya'' (\u845b\u7f85\u679d\u7259) ([[Middle Chinese]] [[Zhengzhang Shangfang|ZS]]: *''k\u0251t\u031a-l\u0251-t\u0361\u0255i\u1d07-\u014b\u02e0a''), whose [[tamga]] is depicted as [[File:AlachinGe-lo-chji27Zuev.gif]].<ref>Zuev Yu.A., ''\"Horse Tamgas from Vassal Princedoms (translation of Chinese composition \"Tanghuiyao\" of the 8th to 10th centuries)\"'', Kazakh SSR Academy of Sciences, Alma-Ata, 1960, pp. 124, 132 (in Russian).</ref>. [[Yury Zuev|Zuev]] amended this to ''Eluozhi'' (MC: *''a-la-tsie'') and asserted that this is the earliest transmission and certainly ascends to Alagchin (Alachin, Alchin, Alchi). During the Tang period, Chinese chroniclers calqued the ethonym Alat as ''Boma'' \"skewbald horses\"<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Zuev Yu.A., ''\"Horse Tamgas from Vassal Princedoms\"'', p. 124</ref> and *''Bi-la'', meaning unknown.\n\n==History==\n\n===Southern Xiongnu in China===\n''[[Tongdian]]'' states that around 349-370 CE a leader of Southern Xiongnu Helou Tou (i.e. Alat Tou), with a title Shanyu, brought his tribe of 35 thousand people to the [[Former Yan]] [[Xianbei]] state and submitted to its dynasty. The Shanyu Helai Tou was bestowed a title of General Pacifying the West, and settled in the Daizong district. It adds that apparently, the tribe Yantuo are their descendants. Yantuo lived intermixed with the tribe [[Xue (surname)|Xue]], therefore they are called ''[[Xueyantuo]]'', that surname of Kagan clan was Ili-tu, that from generation to generation Xueyantuo were a strong [[Tiele people|Tiele]] tribe<ref>Du You, ''Tongdian (\"Collection of the government statutes\") // Series \"Shi Tup\", Ch. 199;'' in\nCen Zhongmian. ''Tujue ji shi'' (collection of materials on history of T\u00fcrk\u00fct). Peking, 1958. p. 695, 697</ref> [[Fang Xuanling]] in ''[[Jin Shu]]'' stated that ''Helai'' (Alats) were one of 19 tribes of the Southern Xiongnu Shanyu.<ref>Fang Xuanling, \"Jin Shu\", ''Series \"Bo-na\"'', Peking, 1958, Ch. 97. p. 66b, l. 11b</ref>\n\nAccording to the Chinese annals, the home of the Eastern Xiongnu tribe Alat was in the basin of the [[Narym River]]. From the Alat tribe originated one of the Eastern Xiongnu Shanyu called Helou Tou, i.e. Alat Tou, most likely named after his maternal tribe. ''Tangshu'' tells about Alats:\n: \"They are north from the [[G\u00f6kt\u00fcrks|T\u00fcrks]], 14,000 li from the Chinese capital. They follow grass and water, but mostly live in the mountains. Their standing army is 30,000 men. There is always snow, and foliage does not fall down. They plough fields with horses. All horses are skewbald colors, therefore the state is also given the same name. They live in the north near a sea. Though they have horses, they do not ride them, but use their milk for food. They are frequently at war with Kirgizes\".\n\n===Alat as a component tribe===\n''Jiu Tangshu'' mentions a tribe of skewbald horses among [[Basmyl]]s, [[Yenisei Kyrgyz|Kirguts]], [[Tuhsi]], etc., who in 638, submitted to the Western T\u00fcrkic ''[[Duolu Qaghan]]''. ''Tongdian'' cites as a comment a fragment from an unknown composition that \"Tuj\u00fce (T\u00fcrks) call the skewbald horses ''e-la (\u0430-la)'', and the state is also called ''\"e-la\"''.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nUnder Arabicized name \"Khalaj\" the Alats are known to constitute one of the major tribes of the 5th-6th century CE [[Hephthalites]].<ref>Kurbanov A.D., \"''Hephthalites: (essays on history)''\", St. Petersburg, European House, 2006, {{ISBN|5-8015-0203-3}}; PhD thesis [http://www.diss.fu-berlin.de/diss/receive/FUDISS_thesis_000000016150]</ref>\n\n===Middle Ages===\nFrom the story of [[Abu al-Ghazi Bahadur|Abulgazi]] and description of two [[Mongolia]]n embassies (in 1233 and 1254) to Alachins, they lived along Yenisei, the sources of Angara, and the east coast of lake Baikal, called by the Chinese chroniclers \"Northern sea\". Based on annalistic traditions, the author of the \"Family tree of T\u00fcrks\" Abulgazi described the country of skewbald horses:\n: \"A multitude of Tatar tribes coached along the banks of the Angara-muren, which runs east of the Kirgiz country and runs into the sea. On the seacoast at the estuary of this river is a large city surrounded by settlements where live nomadic tribes in large numbers. Their horses are large... All of them are skewbald in hue, there are no others. Near that city called Alakchin was a silver spring, therefore all caldrons, dishes, and vases were from silver. It is that country that the Uzbeks mean when say: \"there is a country where all horses are skewbald, and the stoves are from gold\".<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\nThe Khalj\u012b tribe had long been settled in [[Afghanistan]].<ref name=\"Britannica\">[http://www.britannica.com/eb/article-9045252/Khalji-Dynasty Khalji Dynasty]. ''[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]'' Online. 2010. 23 August 2010.</ref> A [[Khalji dynasty|Khalji]] dynasty of Turkic Khalaj origin ruled large parts of South Asia from 1290 to 1320, they were the second Muslim dynasty to rule the [[Delhi Sultanate]] of [[India]], they are noted in history for repeatedly defeating the warring [[Mongols]] and thereby saving India from plundering raids and attacks.<ref>{{cite book |title=The state at war in South Asia |last1=Barua |first1= Pradeep |volume= illustrated |year=2005 |publisher=U of Nebraska Press |isbn=978-0-8032-1344-9 |page=29 of 437 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=FIIQhuAOGaIC&pg=PA29&source=gbs_toc_r&cad=3 |accessdate= 2010-08-23}}</ref>\n\n===Modern time===\nAfter the Russian revolution in 1917, Alats (Kazakh: Ala\u015f), named after a legendary founder of the Kazakh people, headed a movement of the Turkestan peoples for independence, and created a functioning state of the Kazakh people known as [[Alash Autonomy]] that operated between December 13, 1917, and August 26, 1920, controlling roughly the territory of the present-day Republic of Kazakhstan, with a capital in Alash-qala (modern [[Semey]]). The Alash leaders in December 1917 proclaimed establishment of Alash Orda, a Kazakh government, aligned with the Russian White Army and fought against the [[Bolsheviks]].\n\nIn 1919, when the White forces were losing, Alash Autonomous government began negotiations with the Bolsheviks. In 1919\u201320 Bolsheviks defeated the White Russian forces in the region and occupied Kazakhstan. On August 26, 1920, the new Soviet government disbanded the Alash Autonomy, and established the \"Kyrgyz Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republic\", later the name was changed in 1925 to \"Kazak Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republic\" and changed again in 1936 to \"Kazakh Soviet Socialist Republic\". However, the movement for independence continued, and it continued until 1925, when the war for independence was finally extinguished\n\n==Modern demographics==\nThe hsitorical Alats' descedants now live in Russia in the Altai, Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, Turkey, eastern section of the Iranian plateau, India, and Afghanistan.\n\nAlats are also the  main ethnic component in the KazakhJunior [[Zhuz]] and constitute parts of [[Uzbeks]]. Furtehr west, Alats constitute one [[Oghuz Turks|Oghuz Turkish]] tribe, ''Ulayundlu\u011f'' in [[Turkish language|Turkish]] and ''Alayuntluq'' in [[Azerbaijani language|Azeri]], which means \"with spotted horses\"; now they live in central Turkey.\n\nAs of 2000, approximately 42,000 speakers of the [[Khalaj language]] lived in Iran, per ISO 639-3 their language is called Turkic Khalaj, to distinguish it from the Indo-Iranian \"Khalaj\" language. In the Causacus, in Armenia and [[Azerbaijan]] are a number of settlements with the name ascending to the Alats; they also are in Uzbekistan and Tatarstan, and in the form ''Kalat'' in [[Khorasan Province|Khorasan]]. In Afghanistan, Alats are known as one of the largest Pashtun tribes, the [[Ghilzai]]s; they were pasturing at the Ghazni plateau. In India, Alats are called Ghalzae. In Khorasan, Alats are called Kalat, \n\n==Linguistic distinction==\nPrincipal linguistic work on Alat language ([[Khalaj language|Khalaj]] in modern [[Iran]]) was done by [[Gerhard Doerfer]], who posited a non-[[Oghuz languages|Oguz]] classification based on specific features such as preservation of three vowel lengths, preservation of word-initial ''*h'', and lack of the sound change ''*d > y''. An example of these features is the word ''hadaq'' (\"foot\"), which has preserved the initial ''*h'' and medial ''*d'', versus the Oguz form ''ayaq''. Therefore Alat is an independent language that became distinct very early from the Oguz Turkic languages.<ref>Doerfer 1971</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ataturk.com/content/view/55/89/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-02-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081109062059/http://www.ataturk.com/content/view/55/89/ |archivedate=2008-11-09}}</ref> Because of these distinct features, scholars speculated that the Alat (''Khalaj'') is a descendant of the [[Oghur languages|Ogur]] branch of the Turkic family, but there is no firm scholarly consensus on its affinities.\n\n==See also==\n*[[History of Afghanistan]]\n*[[History of China]]\n*[[History of Kazakhstan]]\n*[[Alash Orda]]\n*[[History of Kyrgyzstan]]\n*[[History of Mongolia]]\n*[[Mountainous Republic of the Northern Caucasus]]\n*[[Oghur languages]]\n*[[Khalaj language]]\n*[[Khalji dynasty|Khalji]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ethnologue.com/show_language.asp?code=klj Khalaj, Turkic]\n* [http://www.language-archives.org/language/klj Resources in and about the Turkic Khalaj language]\n* [http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/316083/Khalaj-language Khalaj language]\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{Cite book | last =Doerfer | first =Gerhard | publication-date =1971 | title =Khalaj Materials | publication-place =Bloomington, Indiana | publisher =Indiana University Publications | isbn =0-87750-150-5 | oclc =240052}}\n*{{cite book | author=Doerfer, Gerhard | title=Grammatik des Chaladsch |location=Wiesbaden | publisher=Harrassowitz | year=1998 | isbn=3-447-02865-3}}\n*{{cite book |author1=Doerfer, Gerhard |author2=Tezcan, Semih | title=Folklore-Texte der Chaladsch| location=Wiesbaden| publisher=Harrassowitz| year=1994}}\n*{{cite book |author1=Johanson, Lars |author2=Csat\u00f3, \u00c9va \u00c1gnes | title=The Turkic Languages | location=London | publisher=Routledge | year=1998}}\n\n{{Turkic languages}}\n{{Turkic topics}}\n{{Turkic peoples}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alat (Tribe)}}\n[[Category:Turkic peoples of Asia]]\n", "text_old": "'''Alat''' (a.k.a '''Ala-at''', '''Ala''', '''Alachin''', '''Alagchin''', '''Alchin''', '''Alchi''', '''Alayuntlqu''', '''Ulayundlu\u011f''' (''\"[[piebald]] horse\"'', pinto); '''Boma''' \u99c1\u99ac \"piebald horse\", '''Helai''' \u8cc0\u8cf4, '''Helan''' \u8cc0\u862d, '''Hela''', '''Bila''') are one of the salient [[Turkic peoples|Turkic]] tribes known from Chinese annals, Bactrian inscriptions,<ref>Sims-Williams (2005). ''Some Bactrian Seal-Inscriptions // Afghanistan, ancien carrefour entre l\u2019est et l\u2019ouest'', ed. O. Bopearachchi and M.-F.  Boussac, pp. 335\u201346</ref> and [[Arab]] and [[Persian people|Persian]] medieval geographers as a prominent tribe that played a distinguished role in the history of Eurasia.They are also known as Khalaj, and Khalaches.\n\nLiterature on Alats is very rich; Alats were a subject of study by ''[[Old Book of Tang|Tangshu]]'',  ''[[Jiu Tangshu]]'', ''[[Tang Huiyao]]'', N.Ya. Bichurin, S.E. Malov, N.A. Aristov, [[Grigory Grum-Grshimailo]], Yu. Nemeth, G. H\u043eworth, P. Pelliot, L. Hambis, and others.\n\n==Name==\nIn ancient Turkic lexicon, the meaning of \"[[skewbald]]\" (horse) is expressed with the terms \"''ala''\" or \"''alagchin''\" still active now in composite expressions. Tang Huiyao mentioned, right after the [[Ashina tribe]], a tribe named ''Geluozhiya'' (\u845b\u7f85\u679d\u7259) ([[Middle Chinese]] [[Zhengzhang Shangfang|ZS]]: *''k\u0251t\u031a-l\u0251-t\u0361\u0255i\u1d07-\u014b\u02e0a''), whose [[tamga]] is depicted as [[File:AlachinGe-lo-chji27Zuev.gif]].<ref>Zuev Yu.A., ''\"Horse Tamgas from Vassal Princedoms (translation of Chinese composition \"Tanghuiyao\" of the 8th to 10th centuries)\"'', Kazakh SSR Academy of Sciences, Alma-Ata, 1960, pp. 124, 132 (in Russian).</ref>. [[Yury Zuev|Zuev]] amended this to ''Eluozhi'' (MC: *''a-la-tsie'') and asserted that this is the earliest transmission and certainly ascends to Alagchin (Alachin, Alchin, Alchi). During the Tang period, the Chinese chroniclers calqued the ethonym Alat as ''Boma'' \"skewbald horses\".<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Zuev Yu.A., ''\"Horse Tamgas from Vassal Princedoms\"'', p. 124</ref> and *''Bi-la'', meaning unknown.\n\n==History==\n\n===Southern Xiongnu in China===\n''[[Tongdian]]'' states that around 349-370 CE a leader of Southern Xiongnu Helou Tou (i.e. Alat Tou), with a title Shanyu, brought his tribe of 35 thousand people to the [[Former Yan]] [[Xianbei]] state and submitted to its dynasty. The Shanyu Helai Tou was bestowed a title of General Pacifying the West, and settled in the Daizong district. It adds that apparently, the tribe Yantuo are their descendants. Yantuo lived intermixed with the tribe [[Xue (surname)|Xue]], therefore they are called ''[[Xueyantuo]]'', that surname of Kagan clan was Ili-tu, that from generation to generation Xueyantuo were a strong [[Tiele people|Tiele]] tribe<ref>Du You, ''Tongdian (\"Collection of the government statutes\") // Series \"Shi Tup\", Ch. 199;'' in\nCen Zhongmian. ''Tujue ji shi'' (collection of materials on history of T\u00fcrk\u00fct). Peking, 1958. p. 695, 697</ref> [[Fang Xuanling]] in ''[[Jin Shu]]'' stated that ''Helai'' (Alats) were one of 19 tribes of the Southern Xiongnu Shanyu.<ref>Fang Xuanling, \"Jin Shu\", ''Series \"Bo-na\"'', Peking, 1958, Ch. 97. p. 66b, l. 11b</ref>\n\nAccording to the Chinese annals, the home of the Eastern Xiongnu tribe Alat was in the basin of the [[Narym River]]. From the Alat tribe originated one of the Eastern Xiongnu Shanyu called Helou Tou, i.e. Alat Tou, most likely named after his maternal tribe. ''Tangshu'' tells about Alats:\n: \"They are north from the [[G\u00f6kt\u00fcrks|T\u00fcrks]], 14,000 li from the Chinese capital. They follow grass and water, but mostly live in the mountains. Their standing army is 30,000 men. There is always snow, and foliage does not fall down. They plough fields with horses. All horses are skewbald colors, therefore the state is also given the same name. They live in the north near a sea. Though they have horses, they do not ride them, but use their milk for food. They are frequently at war with Kirgizes\".\n\n===Alat as a component tribe===\n''Jiu Tangshu'' mentions a tribe of skewbald horses among [[Basmyl]]s, [[Yenisei Kyrgyz|Kirguts]], [[Tuhsi]], etc., who in 638, submitted to the Western T\u00fcrkic ''[[Duolu Qaghan]]''. ''Tongdian'' cites as a comment a fragment from an unknown composition that \"Tuj\u00fce (T\u00fcrks) call the skewbald horses ''e-la (\u0430-la)'', and the state is also called ''\"e-la\"''.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nUnder Arabicized name \"Khalaj\" the Alats are known to constitute one of the major tribes of the 5th-6th century CE [[Hephthalites]].<ref>Kurbanov A.D., \"''Hephthalites: (essays on history)''\", St. Petersburg, European House, 2006, {{ISBN|5-8015-0203-3}}; PhD thesis [http://www.diss.fu-berlin.de/diss/receive/FUDISS_thesis_000000016150]</ref>\n\n===Middle Ages===\nFrom the story of [[Abu al-Ghazi Bahadur|Abulgazi]] and description of two [[Mongolia]]n embassies (in 1233 and 1254) to Alachins, they lived along Yenisei, the sources of Angara, and the east coast of lake Baikal, called by the Chinese chroniclers \"Northern sea\". Based on annalistic traditions, the author of the \"Family tree of T\u00fcrks\" Abulgazi described the country of skewbald horses:\n: \"A multitude of Tatar tribes coached along the banks of the Angara-muren, which runs east of the Kirgiz country and runs into the sea. On the seacoast at the estuary of this river is a large city surrounded by settlements where live nomadic tribes in large numbers. Their horses are large... All of them are skewbald in hue, there are no others. Near that city called Alakchin was a silver spring, therefore all caldrons, dishes, and vases were from silver. It is that country that the Uzbeks mean when say: \"there is a country where all horses are skewbald, and the stoves are from gold\".<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\nThe Khalj\u012b tribe had long been settled in [[Afghanistan]].<ref name=\"Britannica\">[http://www.britannica.com/eb/article-9045252/Khalji-Dynasty Khalji Dynasty]. ''[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]'' Online. 2010. 23 August 2010.</ref> A [[Khalji dynasty|Khalji]] dynasty of Turkic Khalaj origin ruled large parts of South Asia from 1290 to 1320, they were the second Muslim dynasty to rule the [[Delhi Sultanate]] of [[India]], they are noted in history for repeatedly defeating the warring [[Mongols]] and thereby saving India from plundering raids and attacks.<ref>{{cite book |title=The state at war in South Asia |last1=Barua |first1= Pradeep |volume= illustrated |year=2005 |publisher=U of Nebraska Press |isbn=978-0-8032-1344-9 |page=29 of 437 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=FIIQhuAOGaIC&pg=PA29&source=gbs_toc_r&cad=3 |accessdate= 2010-08-23}}</ref>\n\n===Modern time===\nAfter the Russian revolution in 1917, Alats (Kazakh: Ala\u015f), named after a legendary founder of the Kazakh people, headed a movement of the Turkestan peoples for independence, and created a functioning state of the Kazakh people known as [[Alash Autonomy]] that operated between December 13, 1917, and August 26, 1920, controlling roughly the territory of the present-day Republic of Kazakhstan, with a capital in Alash-qala (modern [[Semey]]). The Alash leaders in December 1917 proclaimed establishment of Alash Orda, a Kazakh government, aligned with the Russian White Army and fought against the [[Bolsheviks]].\n\nIn 1919, when the White forces were losing, Alash Autonomous government began negotiations with the Bolsheviks. In 1919\u201320 Bolsheviks defeated the White Russian forces in the region and occupied Kazakhstan. On August 26, 1920, the new Soviet government disbanded the Alash Autonomy, and established the \"Kyrgyz Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republic\", later the name was changed in 1925 to \"Kazak Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republic\" and changed again in 1936 to \"Kazakh Soviet Socialist Republic\". However, the movement for independence continued, and it continued until 1925, when the war for independence was finally extinguished\n\n==Modern demographics==\nThe hsitorical Alats' descedants now live in Russia in the Altai, Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, Turkey, eastern section of the Iranian plateau, India, and Afghanistan.\n\nAlats are also the  main ethnic component in the KazakhJunior [[Zhuz]] and constitute parts of [[Uzbeks]]. Furtehr west, Alats constitute one [[Oghuz Turks|Oghuz Turkish]] tribe, ''Ulayundlu\u011f'' in [[Turkish language|Turkish]] and ''Alayuntluq'' in [[Azerbaijani language|Azeri]], which means \"with spotted horses\"; now they live in central Turkey.\n\nAs of 2000, approximately 42,000 speakers of the [[Khalaj language]] lived in Iran, per ISO 639-3 their language is called Turkic Khalaj, to distinguish it from the Indo-Iranian \"Khalaj\" language. In the Causacus, in Armenia and [[Azerbaijan]] are a number of settlements with the name ascending to the Alats; they also are in Uzbekistan and Tatarstan, and in the form ''Kalat'' in [[Khorasan Province|Khorasan]]. In Afghanistan, Alats are known as one of the largest Pashtun tribes, the [[Ghilzai]]s; they were pasturing at the Ghazni plateau. In India, Alats are called Ghalzae. In Khorasan, Alats are called Kalat, \n\n==Linguistic distinction==\nPrincipal linguistic work on Alat language ([[Khalaj language|Khalaj]] in modern [[Iran]]) was done by [[Gerhard Doerfer]], who posited a non-[[Oghuz languages|Oguz]] classification based on specific features such as preservation of three vowel lengths, preservation of word-initial ''*h'', and lack of the sound change ''*d > y''. An example of these features is the word ''hadaq'' (\"foot\"), which has preserved the initial ''*h'' and medial ''*d'', versus the Oguz form ''ayaq''. Therefore Alat is an independent language that became distinct very early from the Oguz Turkic languages.<ref>Doerfer 1971</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ataturk.com/content/view/55/89/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-02-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081109062059/http://www.ataturk.com/content/view/55/89/ |archivedate=2008-11-09}}</ref> Because of these distinct features, scholars speculated that the Alat (''Khalaj'') is a descendant of the [[Oghur languages|Ogur]] branch of the Turkic family, but there is no firm scholarly consensus on its affinities.\n\n==See also==\n*[[History of Afghanistan]]\n*[[History of China]]\n*[[History of Kazakhstan]]\n*[[Alash Orda]]\n*[[History of Kyrgyzstan]]\n*[[History of Mongolia]]\n*[[Mountainous Republic of the Northern Caucasus]]\n*[[Oghur languages]]\n*[[Khalaj language]]\n*[[Khalji dynasty|Khalji]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ethnologue.com/show_language.asp?code=klj Khalaj, Turkic]\n* [http://www.language-archives.org/language/klj Resources in and about the Turkic Khalaj language]\n* [http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/316083/Khalaj-language Khalaj language]\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{Cite book | last =Doerfer | first =Gerhard | publication-date =1971 | title =Khalaj Materials | publication-place =Bloomington, Indiana | publisher =Indiana University Publications | isbn =0-87750-150-5 | oclc =240052}}\n*{{cite book | author=Doerfer, Gerhard | title=Grammatik des Chaladsch |location=Wiesbaden | publisher=Harrassowitz | year=1998 | isbn=3-447-02865-3}}\n*{{cite book |author1=Doerfer, Gerhard |author2=Tezcan, Semih | title=Folklore-Texte der Chaladsch| location=Wiesbaden| publisher=Harrassowitz| year=1994}}\n*{{cite book |author1=Johanson, Lars |author2=Csat\u00f3, \u00c9va \u00c1gnes | title=The Turkic Languages | location=London | publisher=Routledge | year=1998}}\n\n{{Turkic languages}}\n{{Turkic topics}}\n{{Turkic peoples}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alat (Tribe)}}\n[[Category:Turkic peoples of Asia]]\n", "name_user": "Erminwin", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eName", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alat_tribe"}
{"title_page": "Bunte Bl\u00e4tter", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n'''''Bunte Bl\u00e4tter''''' (English: ''Colorful Leaves''), [[Opus number|Op.]] 99, is a collection of piano pieces by [[Robert Schumann]] assembled from earlier unpublished pieces after the success of the ''[[Album for the Young]] (Album f\u00fcr die Jugend)'', Op. 68. Upon publication the pieces were issued both as a complete set and individual pieces, the latter in differently colored covers.<ref name=\"Herttrich\">{{harvnb|Herttrich|2009|p=VI & VII}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nRobert Schumann, started work on assembling the collection of pieces that were eventually published as the ''Bunte Bl\u00e4tter'' Op. 99 and ''[[Albumbl\u00e4tter (Schumann)|Albumbl\u00e4tter]]'' Op. 124 in late 1850. His original plan was to publish the pieces as a single collection entitled ''Spreu'' (English: ''Chaff''). When the music publisher F. W. Arnold objected to the proposed title, Schumann decided to split the collection.<ref name=\"MontgomeryP1\">{{harvnb|Montgomery|2007|p=1}}</ref>\n\nAll of the pieces used, were works that Shumann had composed in the past and had either not intended for publication, or had been rejected for publication with earlier sets of pieces.<ref name=\"Ledbetter2008\">{{harvnb|Ledbetter|2008}}</ref> Ernst Herttrich in his preface to the Henle score, comments that the specific criteria the composer used to select the pieces included in either this collection or the succeeding one are unknown, though the pieces are organised loosely from least to most difficult.<ref>{{harvnb|Hettrich|2009|p=VI}}</ref> Dates of composition range from 1834 {{efn|Albumbl\u00e4tter III was originally composed for ''[[Carnaval (Schumann)|Carnaval Op. 9]]''.}} to 1849 .{{efn|The march that closes the set was composed at the same time as the composers ''Vier Marsch'', Op. 76.}}\n\nMany writers have pointed out that several of the pieces had personal associations for the author, for example, the first piece in the collection, was a Christmas greeting the composer had composed for his wife Clara in 1838.<ref name=\"Ledbetter2008\"/><ref name=\"Herttrich\" /><ref name=\"MontgomeryP1\" />\n\n== Movements ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Title<ref>{{cite web|title=Schumann \u2013 ''Bunte Bl\u00e4tter'', op. 99|url=http://www.pianopedia.com/w_331_schumann.aspx|website=pianopedia.com}}</ref> !! Average duration !! [[Key signature]]\n|-\n| St\u00fccke I (''Piece I'')|| 2:20 || A major\n|-\n| St\u00fccke II (''Piece II'')|| 0:50 || E minor\n|-\n| St\u00fccke III (''Piece III'')|| 0:50 || E major\n|-\n| Albumbl\u00e4tter I (''Album Leaf I'')|| 2:00 || F<sup>\u266f</sup> minor\n|-\n| Albumbl\u00e4tter II (''Album Leaf II'')|| 0:40 || B minor\n|-\n| Albumbl\u00e4tter III (''Album Leaf III'')|| 1:50 || A<sup>\u266d</sup> major\n|-\n| Albumbl\u00e4tter IV (''Album Leaf IV'')|| 2:10 || E<sup>\u266d</sup> minor\n|-\n| Albumbl\u00e4tter V (''Album Leaf V'')|| 1:30 || E<sup>\u266d</sup> major\n|-\n| Novelette || 2:50 || B minor\n|-\n| Pr\u00e4ludium (''Prelude'')|| 1:20 || B<sup>\u266d</sup> minor\n|-\n| Marsch (''March'')|| 7:50 || D minor\n|-\n| Abendmusik (''Evening Music'')|| 3:30 || B<sup>\u266d</sup> major\n|-\n| Scherzo || 4:35 || G minor\n|-\n| Geschwindmarsch (''Swiftly March'')|| 3:30 || G minor\n|}\n\n== References ==\n;Notes\n{{notelist}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n;Sources\n* {{cite web|title=Robert Schumann \u2013 ''Coloured Leaves'' (''Bunte Bl\u00e4tter'') op. 99|url=http://www.henle.de/en/detail/index.html?Title=Coloured+Leaves+%28Bunte+Bl%C3%A4tter%29+op.+99_81|work=G. Henle Publishers|last=Herttrich|first=Ernst|year=2009|ref={{harvid|Herttrich|2009}}}}\n* {{cite AV media notes|url=https://www.naxos.com/mainsite/blurbs_reviews.asp?item_code=8.550680&catNum=550680&filetype=About%20this%20Recording&language=English#|last=Anderson|first=Keith|title=Schumann, R.:Fantasie Op. 17/Bunte Blatter Op. 99|publisher=Naxos Records|type=CD|id=8.550680|year=1993|ref={{harvid|Anderson|1993}}}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.emmanuelmusic.org/notes_translations/program_notes/07-08/schumann_4_notes.htm|last=Ledbetter|first=Steven|title=Program Note: The Schumann Chamber Series Year Four (Concert IV)|publisher=Emmanuel Music|year=2008|ref={{harvid|Ledbetter|2008}}}}\n* {{cite thesis|last=Montgomery|first=Amanda Elizabeth|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160909222424/http://etd.lsu.edu/docs/available/etd-10072007-130430/unrestricted/amandamontgomerymonograph.pdf|url=http://etd.lsu.edu/docs/available/etd-10072007-130430/unrestricted/amandamontgomerymonograph.pdf|title=A Pedagogical Analysis of Selected Pieces from Albumblatter, Op. 124, by Robert Schumann|year=2007|type=DMA|publisher=Louisiana State University|accessdate=2020-03-29|archivedate=2016-09-09|ref={{harvid|Montgomery|2007}}}}\n* {{cite thesis|last=Rickard-Ford|first=Paul|year=2010|title=Portfolio of Recorded Performances and Exegesis: The Late Piano Works of Robert Schumann|type=PhD|publisher=University of Adelaide|url=https://digital.library.adelaide.edu.au/dspace/bitstream/2440/63083/8/02whole.pdf|access-date=2017-10-15|ref={{harvid|Rickard-Ford|2010}}}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.henle.de/blog/en/2016/12/12/autumnal-thoughts-on-%e2%80%9cbuntes-blatt%e2%80%9d-in-f-sharp-minor-by-robert-schumann/|last=Seiffert|first=Wolf-Dieter|title=Autumnal thoughts on ''Buntes Blatt'' in f-sharp minor by Robert Schumann|publisher=[[G. Henle Verlag]]|date=2016-12-12|accessdate=2020-03-30|ref={{harvid|Sieffert|2016}}}}\n* {{cite thesis|url=https://ruor.uottawa.ca/bitstream/10393/27068/1/MR11441.PDF|last=Vezeau|first=Erica Ablene|year=2005|title=Muscial Messaging in the Early Piano Correspondence between Clara Wieck and Robert Schumann|type=MA|publisher=University of Ottawa|access-date=2020-03-29|ref={{harvid|Vezeau|2005}}}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMSLP|work=Bunte Bl\u00e4tter, Op.99 (Schumann, Robert)|cname=''Bunte Bl\u00e4tter'', Op. 99}}\n* {{YouTube|id=L9jEW4RDX0g|title=Schumann: ''Bunte Bl\u00e4tter'